# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bittern-salt
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bittern-salt/alaea-salt] It is claimed by one author that most alaea salt sold in the United States is produced in California, not in Hawaii.
[src:bittern-salt/alaea-salt] True Hawaiian-made alaea salt is expensive and, before the rise of convenient Internet shopping, was difficult to find elsewhere.
[src:bittern-salt/alaea-salt] Alaea salt gets its characteristic brick-red color from a volcanic Hawaiian clay called *ʻalaea*, which contains some 80 minerals and is rich in iron oxide.
[src:bittern-salt/alberger-process] The **Alberger process** is an industrial method of producing salt from rock salt.
[src:bittern-salt/alberger-process] The Alberger process begins by heating brine under high pressure with a series of heaters.
[src:bittern-salt/alberger-process] Impurities are removed using a tank filled with granite cubes called a graveler.
[src:bittern-salt/alberger-process] When the pressure is released, salt crystals form in a steam-heated evaporation pan.
[src:bittern-salt/alberger-process] This results in pyramid-shaped flake salt, which has low bulk density, high solubility, and good adhesion.
[src:bittern-salt/alberger-process] Clair, Michigan that is the only place in the United States that manufactures such salt using the Alberger process.
[src:bittern-salt/alberger-process] Diamond Crystal Kosher Salt is a brand of salt produced using the Alberger process.
[src:bittern-salt/alberger-process] Because of its shape, density and flavor characteristics, it is often a preferred choice by snack food manufacturers.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] In chemistry, an **alkali** (/ˈælkəlaɪ/ ⓘ; from the Arabic word *al-qaly*, القالِي "saltwort") also **base** is a hydroxide of any of either the alkali metal which are Group I s-block elements, or the alkaline earth metal which are Group II s-block.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] *Alkali* can also be defined as a base that dissolves in water.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] A solution of a soluble base has a pH greater than 7.0.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] The adjectives ***alkaline*** and, less often, ***alkalescent*** are commonly used in English as a synonyms for *basic*, especially for bases soluble in water.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] This broad use of the term is likely to have come about because alkalis were the first bases known to obey the Arrhenius definition of a base, and they are still among the most common bases.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] The word *alkali* is derived from Arabic *al qalīy* (or *alkali*), meaning 'the calcined ashes' (see calcination), referring to the original source of alkaline substances.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] A water-extract of burned plant ashes, called *potash* and composed mostly of potassium carbonate, was mildly basic.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] After heating this substance with calcium hydroxide (*slaked lime*), a far more strongly basic substance known as *caustic potash* (potassium hydroxide) was produced.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] Caustic potash was traditionally used in conjunction with animal fats to produce soft soaps, one of the caustic processes that rendered soaps from fats in the process of saponification, one known since antiquity.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] Plant potash lent the name to the element potassium, which was first derived from caustic potash, and also gave potassium its chemical symbol **K** (from the German name *Kalium*), which ultimately derived from al**k**ali.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] Alkalis are all Arrhenius bases, ones which form hydroxide ions (OH−) when dissolved in water.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] The terms "base" and "alkali" are often used interchangeably, particularly outside the context of chemistry and chemical engineering.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] There are various, more specific definitions for the concept of an alkali.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] Alkalis are usually defined as a subset of the bases.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] The second subset of bases is also called an "Arrhenius base".
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] Soils with pH values that are higher than 7.3 are usually defined as being alkaline.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] These soils can occur naturally due to the presence of alkali salts.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] Although many plants do prefer slightly basic soil (including vegetables like cabbage and fodder like buffalo grass), most plants prefer mildly acidic soil (with pHs between 6.0 and 6.8), and alkaline soils can cause problems.
[src:bittern-salt/alkali] In alkali lakes (also called *soda lakes*), evaporation concentrates the naturally occurring carbonate salts, giving rise to an alkalic and often saline lake.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In the United States, Western Europe, and Japan, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 2021, prices for industrial metals such as aluminium have soared to near-record levels as energy shortages in China drive up costs for electricity.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The names *aluminium* and *aluminum* are derived from the word *alumine*, an obsolete term for *alumina*, the primary naturally occurring oxide of aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] *Alumine* was borrowed from French, which in turn derived it from *alumen*, the classical Latin name for alum, the mineral from which it was collected.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The Latin word *alumen* stems from the Proto-Indo-European root **alu-* meaning "bitter" or "beer".
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The English name *alum* does not come directly from Latin, whereas *alumine*/*alumina* comes from the Latin word *alumen* (on declension, *alumen* changes to *alumin-*).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] British chemist Humphry Davy, who performed a number of experiments aimed to isolate the metal, is credited as the person who named the element.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The first name proposed for the metal to be isolated from alum was *alumium*, which Davy suggested in an 1808 article on his electrochemical research, published in Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It appeared that the name was created from the English word *alum* and the Latin suffix *-ium*; but it was customary then to give elements names originating in Latin, so this name was not adopted universally.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The name *alumium* was criticized by contemporary chemists from France, Germany, and Sweden, who insisted the metal should be named for the oxide, alumina, from which it would be isolated.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] One example was *Essai sur la Nomenclature chimique* (July 1811), written in French by a Swedish chemist, Jöns Jacob Berzelius, in which the name *aluminium* is given to the element that would be synthesized from alum.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] (Another article in the same journal issue also refers to the metal whose oxide is the basis of sapphire, i.e., the same metal, as to *aluminium*.) A January 1811 summary of one of Davy's lectures at the Royal Society mentioned the name *aluminium* as a possibility.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 1812, Davy published his chemistry text *Elements of Chemical Philosophy* in which he used the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 1812, British scientist Thomas Young wrote an anonymous review of Davy's book, in which he proposed the name *aluminium* instead of *aluminum*, which he thought had a "less classical sound".
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] This name persisted: although the *-um* spelling was occasionally used in Britain, the American scientific language used *-ium* from the start.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The French have used the spelling *aluminium* from the start.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Most scientists throughout the world used *-ium* in the 19th century; and it was entrenched in several other European languages, such as French, German, and Dutch.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 1828, an American lexicographer, Noah Webster, entered only the *aluminum* spelling in his *American Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In the 1830s, the *-um* spelling gained usage in the United States; by the 1860s, it had become the more common spelling there outside science.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 1892, Hall used the *-um* spelling in his advertising handbill for his new electrolytic method of producing the metal, despite his constant use of the *-ium* spelling in all the patents he filed between 1886 and 1903.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is unknown whether this spelling was introduced by mistake or intentionally, but Hall preferred *aluminum* since its introduction because it resembled *platinum*, the name of a prestigious metal.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] By 1890, both spellings had been common in the United States, the *-ium* spelling being slightly more common; by 1895, the situation had reversed; by 1900, *aluminum* had become twice as common as *aluminium*; in the next decade, the *-um* spelling dominated American usage.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 1925, the American Chemical Society adopted the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted *aluminium* as the standard international name for the element in 1990.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In 1993, they recognized *aluminum* as an acceptable variant; the most recent 2005 edition of the IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry also acknowledges this spelling.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] IUPAC official publications use the *-ium* spelling as primary, and they list both where it is appropriate.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Their usage is currently regional: *aluminum* dominates in the United States and Canada; *aluminium* is prevalent in the rest of the English-speaking world.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] German physicist Ludwig Wilhelm Gilbert had proposed *Thonerde-metall*, after the German *Thonerde* for alumina, in his *Annalen der Physik* but that name never caught on at all even in Germany.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Richards in 1891 found just one occurrence of *argillium* in Swedish, from the French *argille* for clay.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The production of aluminium starts with the extraction of bauxite rock from the ground.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The bauxite is processed and transformed using the Bayer process into alumina, which is then processed using the Hall–Héroult process, resulting in the final aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production is highly energy-consuming, and so the producers tend to locate smelters in places where electric power is both plentiful and inexpensive.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Production of one kilogram of aluminium requires 7 kilograms of oil energy equivalent, as compared to 1.5 kilograms for steel and 2 kilograms for plastic.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] As of 2024, the world's largest producers of aluminium were China, India, Russia, Canada, and the United Arab Emirates, while China is by far the top producer of aluminium with a world share of over 55%.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] According to the International Resource Panel's Metal Stocks in Society report, the global per capita stock of aluminium in use in society (i.e. in cars, buildings, electronics, etc.) is 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Much of this is in more-developed countries (350–500 kg (770–1,100 lb) per capita) rather than less-developed countries (35 kg (77 lb) per capita).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is converted to alumina by the Bayer process.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is blended for uniform composition and then is ground fine.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] After this reaction, the slurry is at a temperature above its atmospheric boiling point.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is cooled by removing steam as pressure is reduced.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The bauxite residue is separated from the solution and discarded.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The solution, free of solids, is seeded with small crystals of aluminium hydroxide; this causes decomposition of the [Al(OH)4]− ions to aluminium hydroxide.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] After about half of aluminium has precipitated, the mixture is sent to classifiers.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Small crystals of aluminium hydroxide are collected to serve as seeding agents; coarse particles are converted to alumina by heating; the excess solution is removed by evaporation, (if needed) purified, and recycled.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The conversion of alumina to aluminium is achieved by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] In this energy-intensive process, a solution of alumina in a molten (940 and 970 °C (1,720 and 1,780 °F)) mixture of cryolite (Na3AlF6) with calcium fluoride is electrolyzed to produce metallic aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The liquid aluminium sinks to the bottom of the solution and is tapped off, and usually cast into large blocks called aluminium billets for further processing.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Anodes of the electrolysis cell are made of carbon—the most resistant material against fluoride corrosion—and either bake at the process or are prebaked.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The former, also called Söderberg anodes, are less power-efficient and fumes released during baking are costly to collect, which is why they are being replaced by prebaked anodes even though they save the power, energy, and labor to prebake the cathodes.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Carbon for anodes should be preferably pure so that neither aluminium nor the electrolyte is contaminated with ash.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Despite carbon's resistivity against corrosion, it is still consumed at a rate of 0.4–0.5 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Cathodes are made of anthracite; high purity for them is not required because impurities leach only very slowly.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The cathode is consumed at a rate of 0.02–0.04 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] A cell is usually terminated after 2–6 years following a failure of the cathode.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Heroult process produces aluminium with a purity of above 99%.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Further purification can be done by the Hoopes process.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] This process involves the electrolysis of molten aluminium with a sodium, barium, and aluminium fluoride electrolyte.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The resulting aluminium has a purity of 99.99%.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Electric power represents about 20 to 40% of the cost of producing aluminium, depending on the location of the smelter.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production consumes roughly 5% of electricity generated in the United States.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Because of this, alternatives to the Hall–Héroult process have been researched, but none has turned out to be economically feasible.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Recovery of the metal through recycling has become an important task of the aluminium industry.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Recycling was a low-profile activity until the late 1960s, when the growing use of aluminium beverage cans brought it to public awareness.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Recycling involves melting the scrap, a process that requires only 5% of the energy used to produce aluminium from ore, though a significant part (up to 15% of the input material) is lost as dross (ash-like oxide).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] An aluminium stack melter produces significantly less dross, with values reported below 1%.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] White dross from primary aluminium production and from secondary recycling operations still contains useful quantities of aluminium that can be extracted industrially.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases including, among others, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide and significant amounts of ammonia.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Despite these difficulties, the waste is used as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Its potential for hydrogen production has also been considered and researched.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The global production of aluminium in 2016 was 58.8 million metric tons.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It exceeded that of any other metal except iron (1,231 million metric tons).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is almost always alloyed, which markedly improves its mechanical properties, especially when tempered.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] For example, the common aluminium foils and beverage cans are alloys of 92% to 99% aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The main alloying agents for both wrought and cast aluminium are copper, zinc, magnesium, manganese, and silicon (e.g., duralumin) with the levels of other metals in a few percent by weight.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is the main substitute to copper and its applications to the traditional domains of copper have seen increased interest when copper prices are high such as in 2011–2014 and 2021.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] There is a competition in the use of aluminium and copper in the automotive industry, but in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables aluminium has been largely unable to compete with copper.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The great majority (about 90%) of aluminium oxide is converted to metallic aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Being a very hard material (Mohs hardness 9), alumina is widely used as an abrasive; being extraordinarily chemically inert, it is useful in highly reactive environments such as high pressure sodium lamps.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium oxide is commonly used as a catalyst for industrial processes; e.g. the Claus process to convert hydrogen sulfide to sulfur in refineries and to alkylate amines.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Many industrial catalysts are supported by alumina, meaning that the expensive catalyst material is dispersed over a surface of the inert alumina.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Another principal use is as a drying agent or absorbent.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Several sulfates of aluminium have industrial and commercial application.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium sulfate (in its hydrate form) is produced on the annual scale of several millions of metric tons.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] About two-thirds is consumed in water treatment.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] The next major application is in the manufacture of paper.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] It is also used as a mordant in dyeing, in pickling seeds, deodorizing of mineral oils, in leather tanning, and in production of other aluminium compounds.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Two kinds of alum, ammonium alum and potassium alum, were formerly used as mordants and in leather tanning, but their use has significantly declined following availability of high-purity aluminium sulfate.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Anhydrous aluminium chloride is used as a catalyst in chemical and petrochemical industries, the dyeing industry, and in synthesis of various inorganic and organic compounds.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxychlorides are used in purifying water, in the paper industry, and as antiperspirants.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p01] Sodium aluminate is used in treating water and as an accelerator of solidification of cement.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Despite its widespread occurrence in the Earth's crust, aluminium has no known function in biology.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] At pH 6–9 (relevant for most natural waters), aluminium precipitates out of water as the hydroxide and is hence not available; most elements behaving this way have no biological role or are toxic.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Aluminium sulfate has an LD50 of 6207 mg/kg (oral, mouse).
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is classified as a non-carcinogen by the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] A review published in 1988 said that there was little evidence that normal exposure to aluminium presents a risk to healthy adult, and a 2014 multi-element toxicology review was unable to find deleterious effects of aluminium consumed in amounts not greater than 40 mg/day per kg of body mass.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Most ingested aluminium is eliminated in feces, and much of what enters the bloodstream is excreted in urine; however, not all absorbed or parenterally administered aluminium is cleared through urinary excretion.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Aluminium, although rarely, can cause vitamin D-resistant osteomalacia, erythropoietin-resistant microcytic anemia, and central nervous system alterations.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] People with kidney insufficiency are especially at a risk.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Chronic ingestion of hydrated aluminium silicates (for excess gastric acidity control) may result in aluminium binding to intestinal contents and increased elimination of other metals, such as iron or zinc; sufficiently high doses (>50 g/day) can cause anemia.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] During the 1988 Camelford water pollution incident, people in Camelford had their drinking water contaminated with aluminium sulfate for several weeks.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] A final report into the incident in 2013 concluded it was unlikely that this had caused long-term health problems.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Aluminium has been suspected of being a possible cause of Alzheimer's disease, but research into this for over 40 years has found, as of 2018, no good evidence of causal effect.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Aluminium increases estrogen-related gene expression in human breast cancer cells cultured in the laboratory.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] In very high doses, aluminium is associated with altered function of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] A small percentage of people have contact allergies to aluminium and experience itchy red rashes, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, poor memory, insomnia, depression, asthma, irritable bowel syndrome, or other symptoms upon contact with products containing aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Exposure to powdered aluminium or aluminium welding fumes can cause pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Fine aluminium powder can ignite or explode, posing another workplace hazard.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Drinking water contains more aluminium than solid food; however, aluminium in food may be absorbed more than aluminium from water.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Dietary exposure in Europeans averages to 0.2–1.5 mg/kg/week but can be as high as 2.3 mg/kg/week.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Higher exposure levels of aluminium are mostly limited to plumbers, masons, electrical workers, machinists, and surgeons.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Consumption of antacids, antiperspirants, vaccines, and cosmetics provide possible routes of exposure.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Consumption of acidic foods or liquids with aluminium enhances aluminium absorption, and maltol has been shown to increase the accumulation of aluminium in nerve and bone tissues.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] In case of suspected sudden intake of a large amount of aluminium, the only treatment is deferoxamine mesylate which may be given to help eliminate aluminium from the body by chelation therapy.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] However, this should be applied with caution as this reduces not only aluminium body levels, but also those of other metals such as copper or iron.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] High levels of aluminium occur near mining sites; small amounts of aluminium are released to the environment at coal-fired power plants or incinerators.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Aluminium in the air is washed out by the rain or normally settles down but small particles of aluminium remain in the air for a long time.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Acidic precipitation is the main natural factor to mobilize aluminium from natural sources and the main reason for the environmental effects of aluminium; however, the main factor of presence of aluminium in salt and freshwater are the industrial processes that also release aluminium into air.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] In water, aluminium acts as a toxic agent on gill-breathing animals such as fish when the water is acidic, in which aluminium may precipitate on gills, which causes loss of plasma- and hemolymph ions leading to osmoregulatory failure.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Organic complexes of aluminium may be easily absorbed and interfere with metabolism in mammals and birds, even though this rarely happens in practice.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is primary among the factors that reduce plant growth on acidic soils.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Although it is generally harmless to plant growth in pH-neutral soils, in acid soils the concentration of toxic Al3+ cations increases and disturbs root growth and function.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Wheat has developed a tolerance to aluminium, releasing organic compounds that bind to harmful aluminium cations.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Sorghum is believed to have the same tolerance mechanism.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Aluminium production possesses its own challenges to the environment on each step of the production process.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] The major challenge is the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] These gases result from electrical consumption of the smelters and the byproducts of processing.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] The most potent of these gases are perfluorocarbons, namely CF4 and C2F6, from the smelting process.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] Biodegradation of metallic aluminium is extremely rare; most aluminium-corroding organisms do not directly attack or consume the aluminium, but instead produce corrosive wastes.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] The fungus *Geotrichum candidum* can consume the aluminium in compact discs.
[src:bittern-salt/aluminium-p02] The bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and the fungus *Cladosporium resinae* are commonly detected in aircraft fuel tanks that use kerosene-based fuels (not avgas), and laboratory cultures can degrade aluminium.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia, either directly or indirectly, is also a building block for the synthesis of many chemicals.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In many countries, it is classified as an extremely hazardous substance.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is toxic, causing damage to cells and tissues.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] For this reason it is excreted by most animals in the urine, in the form of dissolved urea.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is produced biologically in a process called nitrogen fixation, but even more is generated industrially by the Haber process.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The process helped revolutionise agriculture by providing cheap fertilizers.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The global industrial production of ammonia in 2021 was 235 million tonnes.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Industrial ammonia is transported by road in tankers, by rail in tank wagons, by sea in gas carriers, or in cylinders.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia occurs in nature and has been detected in the interstellar medium.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia boils at −33.34 °C (−28.012 °F) at a pressure of one atmosphere, but the liquid can often be handled in the laboratory without external cooling.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Household ammonia or ammonium hydroxide is a solution of ammonia in water.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The name *ammonia* is derived from the name of the Egyptian deity *Amun* (*Ammon* in Greek) since priests and travellers of those temples would burn soils rich in ammonium chloride, which came from animal dung and urine.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Pliny, in Book XXXI of his Natural History, refers to a salt named *hammoniacum*, so called because of the proximity of its source to the Temple of Jupiter Amun (Greek Ἄμμων *Ammon*) in the Roman province of Cyrenaica.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] However, the description Pliny gives of the salt does not conform to the properties of ammonium chloride.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] According to Herbert Hoover's commentary in his English translation of Georgius Agricola's *De re metallica*, it is likely to have been common sea salt.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In any case, that salt ultimately gave ammonia and ammonium compounds their name.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Substances containing ammonia, or those that are similar to it, are called *ammoniacal*.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia arises in the atmosphere from both anthropogenic and natural sources.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The prevalent source is agriculture at around 80%.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] This includes fertilizers, urea produced by livestock, and manure in order of contribution.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Biomass burning also contributes to atmospheric ammonia, with forest fires and agricultural waste burning emitting roughly the same amount of ammonia into the atmosphere.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia can be emitted naturally from soils and plants when the concentration of ammonia in the soil or plant is higher than the concentration of ammonia in the air.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] This is known as one part of the bi-directional exchange model.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The dominant sink for atmospheric ammonia is rain.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In soil, ammonia-oxidizing archaea (AOA) and ammonia-oxidizing bacteria (AOB) convert ammonia into nitrite.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The atmospheric lifetime of ammonia through these processes vary from 12 to 48 hours.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Atmospheric ammonia gives sulfate-nitrate aerosols through reactions with sulfuric acid and nitric acid, with ammonium sulfate being prominent in this process due to its low vapour pressure.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] These aerosols affect the climate and can impact human health.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The lifetime of ammonia through oxidisation is much longer than through deposition, with it being as low as 30 days.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The amino radical then can be oxidised by multiple compounds to form greenhouse gases, such as nitrous oxide.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The oxidation of ammonia may also result in the production of nitric oxide, increasing NOx levels significantly in rural areas where relative levels are typically lower compared to urban areas.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is a colourless gas with a characteristically pungent smell.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It is lighter than air, its density being 0.589 times that of air.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It is easily liquefied due to the strong hydrogen bonding between molecules.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Gaseous ammonia turns to a colourless liquid, which boils at −33.1 °C (−27.58 °F), and freezes to colourless crystals at −77.7 °C (−107.86 °F).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Little data is available at very high temperatures and pressures, but the liquid-vapor critical point occurs at 405 K and 11.35 MPa.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The crystal symmetry is cubic, Pearson symbol cP16, space group P213 No.198, lattice constant 0.5125 nm.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia possesses strong ionising powers reflecting its high *ε* of 22 at −35 °C (−31 °F).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In an aqueous solution, it can be expelled by boiling.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The aqueous solution of ammonia is basic, and may be described as aqueous ammonia or ammonium hydroxide.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The maximum concentration of ammonia in water (a saturated solution) has a specific gravity of 0.880 and is often known as '.880 ammonia'.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia is a widely studied nonaqueous ionising solvent.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Its most conspicuous property is its ability to dissolve alkali metals to form highly coloured, electrically conductive solutions containing solvated electrons.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Apart from these remarkable solutions, much of the chemistry in liquid ammonia can be classified by analogy with related reactions in aqueous solutions.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Comparison of the physical properties of NH3 with those of water shows NH3 has the lower melting point, boiling point, density, viscosity, dielectric constant and electrical conductivity.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] These differences are attributed at least in part to the weaker hydrogen bonding in NH3.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The ionic self-dissociation constant of liquid NH3 at −50 °C is about 10−33.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia is an ionising solvent, although less so than water, and dissolves a range of ionic compounds, including many nitrates, nitrites, cyanides, thiocyanates, metal cyclopentadienyl complexes and metal bis(trimethylsilyl)amides.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Most ammonium salts are soluble and act as acids in liquid ammonia solutions.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The solubility of halide salts increases from fluoride to iodide.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] A saturated solution of ammonium nitrate (**Divers' solution**, named after Edward Divers) contains 0.83 mol solute per mole of ammonia and has a vapour pressure of less than 1 bar even at 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] However, few oxyanion salts with other cations dissolve.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia will dissolve all of the alkali metals and other electropositive metals such as Ca, Sr, Ba, Eu and Yb (also Mg using an electrolytic process).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] At low concentrations (<0.06 mol/L), deep blue solutions are formed: these contain metal cations and solvated electrons, free electrons that are surrounded by a cage of ammonia molecules.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] These solutions are strong reducing agents.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] At higher concentrations, the solutions are metallic in appearance and in electrical conductivity.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] At low temperatures, the two types of solution can coexist as immiscible phases.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In practice, both oxidation to dinitrogen and reduction to dihydrogen are slow, although ammonia in principle is labile under both conditions.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Although oxidation of liquid ammonia is usually slow, there is still a risk of explosion, particularly if transition metal ions are present as possible catalysts.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The stability of ammonia under reducing conditions is evidenced by the slow (hours) decomposition of solutions containing alkali metals.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The ammonia molecule has a trigonal pyramidal shape, as predicted by the valence shell electron pair repulsion theory (VSEPR theory) with an experimentally determined bond angle of 106.7°.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The central nitrogen atom has five outer electrons with an additional electron from each hydrogen atom.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] This gives a total of eight electrons, or four electron pairs that are arranged tetrahedrally.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Three of these electron pairs are used as bond pairs, which leaves one lone pair of electrons.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The lone pair repels more strongly than bond pairs; therefore, the bond angle is not 109.5°, as expected for a regular tetrahedral arrangement, but 106.7°.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] This shape gives the molecule a dipole moment and makes it polar.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The molecule's polarity, and especially its ability to form hydrogen bonds, makes ammonia highly miscible with water.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The lone pair makes ammonia a base, a proton acceptor.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is moderately basic; a 1.0 M aqueous solution has a pH of 11.6, and if a strong acid is added to such a solution until the solution is neutral (pH = 7), 99.4% of the ammonia molecules are protonated.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Temperature and salinity also affect the proportion of ammonium [NH4]+.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The latter has the shape of a regular tetrahedron and is isoelectronic with methane.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The ammonia molecule readily undergoes nitrogen inversion at room temperature; a useful analogy is an umbrella turning itself inside out in a strong wind.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The energy barrier to this inversion is 24.7 kJ/mol, and the resonance frequency is 23.79 GHz, corresponding to microwave radiation of a wavelength of 1.260 cm.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The absorption at this frequency was the first microwave spectrum to be observed and was used in the first maser.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] One of the most characteristic properties of ammonia is its basicity.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is considered to be a weak base.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It combines with acids to form ammonium salts.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Thus, with hydrochloric acid it forms ammonium chloride, with nitric acid, ammonium nitrate, etc.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Perfectly dry ammonia gas will not combine with perfectly dry hydrogen chloride gas; moisture is necessary to bring about the reaction.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Although ammonia is well known as a weak base, it can also act as an extremely weak acid.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It is a protic substance and is capable of formation of amides (which contain the NH−2 ion).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia often functions as a weak base, so it has some buffering ability.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Shifts in pH will cause more or fewer ammonium cations (NH+4) and amide anions (NH−2) to be present in solution.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia does not burn readily or sustain combustion, except under narrow fuel-to-air mixtures of 15–28% ammonia by volume in air.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] When mixed with oxygen, it burns with a pale yellowish-green flame.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ignition occurs when chlorine is passed into ammonia, forming nitrogen and hydrogen chloride; if chlorine is present in excess, then the highly explosive nitrogen trichloride (NCl3) is also formed.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The standard enthalpy change of combustion, Δ*H*°c, expressed per mole of ammonia and with condensation of the water formed, is −382.81 kJ/mol.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Dinitrogen is the thermodynamic product of combustion: all nitrogen oxides are unstable with respect to N2 and O2, which is the principle behind the catalytic converter.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] However, recent studies have shown that efficient and stable combustion of ammonia can be achieved using swirl combustors, thereby rekindling research interest in ammonia as a fuel for thermal power production.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The flammable range of ammonia in dry air is 15.15–27.35% and in 100% relative humidity air is 15.95–26.55%.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] For studying the kinetics of ammonia combustion, knowledge of a detailed reliable reaction mechanism is required, but this has been challenging to obtain.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is a direct or indirect precursor to most manufactured nitrogen-containing compounds.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It is the precursor to nitric acid, which is the source for most N-substituted aromatic compounds.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Its ring-opening reaction with ethylene oxide give ethanolamine, diethanolamine, and triethanolamine.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Amides can be prepared by the reaction of ammonia with carboxylic acid and their derivatives.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] For example, ammonia reacts with formic acid (HCOOH) to yield formamide (HCONH2) when heated.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Acyl chlorides are the most reactive, but the ammonia must be present in at least a twofold excess to neutralise the hydrogen chloride formed.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Esters and anhydrides also react with ammonia to form amides.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonium salts of carboxylic acids can be dehydrated to amides by heating to 150–200 °C as long as no thermally sensitive groups are present.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Other organonitrogen compounds include alprazolam, ethanolamine, ethyl carbamate and hexamethylenetetramine.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Nitric acid is generated via the Ostwald process by oxidation of ammonia with air over a platinum catalyst at 700–850 °C (1,292–1,562 °F), ≈9 atm.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Nitric acid is used for the production of fertilisers, explosives, and many organonitrogen compounds.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The hydrogen in ammonia is susceptible to replacement by a myriad substituents.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] With alkenes and with alcohols, ammonia gives alkylamines.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] With chlorine, monochloramine is formed.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Pentavalent ammonia is known as λ5-amine, nitrogen pentahydride decomposes spontaneously into trivalent ammonia (λ3-amine) and hydrogen gas at normal conditions.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] This substance was once investigated as a possible solid rocket fuel in 1966.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is a ligand forming metal ammine complexes.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] For historical reasons, ammonia is named **ammine** in the nomenclature of coordination compounds.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] One notable ammine complex is cisplatin (Pt(NH3)2Cl2, a widely used anticancer drug.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammine complexes of chromium(III) formed the basis of Alfred Werner's revolutionary theory on the structure of coordination compounds.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Werner noted only two isomers (*fac*- and *mer*-) of the complex [CrCl3(NH3)3] could be formed, and concluded the ligands must be arranged around the metal ion at the vertices of an octahedron.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia forms 1:1 adducts with a variety of Lewis acids such as I2, phenol, and Al(CH3)3.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is a hard base (HSAB theory) and its E & C parameters are EB = 2.31 and CB = 2.04.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Its relative donor strength toward a series of acids, versus other Lewis bases, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Sulfur sticks are burnt to detect small leaks in industrial ammonia refrigeration systems.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In a laboratorial setting, gaseous ammonia can be detected by using concentrated hydrochloric acid or gaseous hydrogen chloride.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] A dense white fume (which is ammonium chloride vapour) arises from the reaction between ammonia and HCl.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The ancient Greek historian Herodotus mentioned that there were outcrops of salt in an area of Libya that was inhabited by a people called the 'Ammonians' (now the Siwa oasis in northwestern Egypt, where salt lakes still exist).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The Greek geographer Strabo also mentioned the salt from this region.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] However, the ancient authors Dioscorides, Apicius, Arrian, Synesius, and Aëtius of Amida described this salt as forming clear crystals that could be used for cooking and that were essentially rock salt.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] *Hammoniacus sal* appears in the writings of Pliny, although it is not known whether the term is equivalent to the more modern sal ammoniac (ammonium chloride).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The fermentation of urine by bacteria produces a solution of ammonia; hence fermented urine was used in Classical Antiquity to wash cloth and clothing, to remove hair from hides in preparation for tanning, to serve as a mordant in dyeing cloth, and to remove rust from iron.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It was also used by ancient dentists to wash teeth.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In the form of sal ammoniac (نشادر, *nushadir*), ammonia was important to the Muslim alchemists.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It was mentioned in the *Book of Stones*, likely written in the 9th century and attributed to Jābir ibn Hayyān.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It was also important to the European alchemists of the 13th century, being mentioned by Albertus Magnus.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It was also used by dyers in the Middle Ages in the form of fermented urine to alter the colour of vegetable dyes.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In the 15th century, Basilius Valentinus showed that ammonia could be obtained by the action of alkalis on sal ammoniac.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] At a later period, when sal ammoniac was obtained by distilling the hooves and horns of oxen and neutralising the resulting carbonate with hydrochloric acid, the name 'spirit of hartshorn' was applied to ammonia.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Gaseous ammonia was first isolated by Joseph Black in 1756 by reacting *sal ammoniac* (ammonium chloride) with *calcined magnesia* (magnesium oxide).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It was isolated again by Peter Woulfe in 1767, by Carl Wilhelm Scheele in 1770 and by Joseph Priestley in 1773 and was termed by him 'alkaline air'.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Eleven years later in 1785, Claude Louis Berthollet ascertained its composition.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The production of ammonia from nitrogen in the air (and hydrogen) was invented by Fritz Haber and Robert LeRossignol.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Later, Carl Bosch developed the industrial method for ammonia production (Haber–Bosch process).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It was first used on an industrial scale in Germany during World War I, following the allied blockade that cut off the supply of nitrates from Chile.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The ammonia was used to produce explosives to sustain war efforts.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The Nobel Prize in Chemistry 1918 was awarded to Fritz Haber "for the synthesis of ammonia from its elements".
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Before the availability of natural gas, hydrogen as a precursor to ammonia production was produced via the electrolysis of water or using the chloralkali process.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] With the advent of the steel industry in the 20th century, ammonia became a byproduct of the production of coking coal.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In the US as of 2019, approximately 88% of ammonia was used as fertilisers either as its salts, solutions or anhydrously.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] When applied to soil, it helps provide increased yields of crops such as maize and wheat.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] 30% of agricultural nitrogen applied in the US is in the form of anhydrous ammonia, and worldwide, 110 million tonnes are applied each year.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Solutions of ammonia ranging from 16% to 25% are used in the fermentation industry as a source of nitrogen for microorganisms and to adjust pH during fermentation.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] African countries aim to use their potential to produce renewable ammonia to reduce their dependence on fertiliser imports.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Because of ammonia's vapourisation properties, it is a useful refrigerant.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It was commonly used before the popularisation of chlorofluorocarbons (Freons).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Anhydrous ammonia is widely used in industrial refrigeration applications and hockey rinks because of its high energy efficiency and low cost.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It suffers from the disadvantage of toxicity, and requiring corrosion resistant components, which restricts its domestic and small-scale use.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Along with its use in modern vapour-compression refrigeration it is used in a mixture along with hydrogen and water in absorption refrigerators.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The Kalina cycle, which is of growing importance to geothermal power plants, depends on the wide boiling range of the ammonia–water mixture.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia coolant is also used in the radiators aboard the International Space Station in loops that are used to regulate the internal temperature and enable temperature-dependent experiments.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The ammonia is under sufficient pressure to remain liquid throughout the process.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Single-phase ammonia cooling systems also serve the power electronics in each pair of solar arrays.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The potential importance of ammonia as a refrigerant has increased with the discovery that vented CFCs and HFCs are potent and stable greenhouse gases.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] As early as in 1895, it was known that ammonia was 'strongly antiseptic; it requires 1.4 grams per litre to preserve beef tea (broth).' In one study, anhydrous ammonia destroyed 99.999% of zoonotic bacteria in three types of animal feed, but not silage.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Anhydrous ammonia is currently used commercially to reduce or eliminate microbial contamination of beef.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Lean finely textured beef (popularly known as 'pink slime') in the beef industry is made from fatty beef trimmings (c.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] 50–70% fat) by removing the fat using heat and centrifugation, then treating it with ammonia to kill *E. coli*.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The process was deemed effective and safe by the US Department of Agriculture based on a study that found that the treatment reduces *E. coli* to undetectable levels.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] There have been safety concerns about the process as well as consumer complaints about the taste and smell of ammonia-treated beef.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia has been used as fuel, and is a proposed alternative to fossil fuels and hydrogen, especially in maritime transport.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Being liquid at ambient temperature under its own vapour pressure and having high volumetric and gravimetric energy density, ammonia is considered a suitable carrier for hydrogen, and may be cheaper than direct transport of liquid hydrogen.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Compared to hydrogen, ammonia is easier to store.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Compared to hydrogen as a fuel, ammonia is much more energy efficient, and could be produced, stored and delivered at a much lower cost than hydrogen, which must be kept compressed or as a cryogenic liquid.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The raw energy density of liquid ammonia is 11.5 MJ/L, which is about a third that of diesel.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia can also be converted back to hydrogen to be used to power hydrogen fuel cells, or it may be used directly within high-temperature solid oxide direct ammonia fuel cells to provide efficient power sources that do not emit greenhouse gases.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia to hydrogen conversion can be achieved through the sodium amide process or the catalytic decomposition of ammonia using solid catalysts.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia production currently creates 1.8% of global CO2 emissions.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] 'Green ammonia' is ammonia produced by using green hydrogen (hydrogen produced by electrolysis with electricity from renewable energy), whereas 'blue ammonia' is ammonia produced using blue hydrogen (hydrogen produced by steam methane reforming) where the carbon dioxide has been captured and stored.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In a world first in 2020, Saudi Arabia shipped 40 metric tons of liquid 'blue ammonia' to Japan for use as a fuel.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It was produced as a by-product by petrochemical industries, and can be burned without giving off greenhouse gases.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Its energy density by volume is nearly double that of liquid hydrogen.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] If the process of creating it can be scaled up via purely renewable resources, producing green ammonia, it could make a major difference in avoiding climate change.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Green ammonia is considered as a potential fuel for new ships, including future container ships.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is expected to increase in usage as a fuel source for shipping The IEA forecasts that ammonia will meet approximately 45% of shipping fuel demands by 2050.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In 2020, the companies DSME and MAN Energy Solutions announced the construction of an ammonia-based ship, DSME plans to commercialise it by 2025.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The use of ammonia as a potential alternative fuel for aircraft jet engines is also being explored.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In addition, hybrid engine configurations for supersonic aviation employing ammonia fuel have been investigated.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Japan is implementing a plan to develop ammonia co-firing technology that can increase the use of ammonia in power generation, as part of efforts to assist domestic and other Asian utilities to accelerate their transition to carbon neutrality.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In October 2021, the first International Conference on Fuel Ammonia (ICFA2021) was held.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In June 2022, IHI Corporation succeeded in reducing greenhouse gases by over 99% during combustion of liquid ammonia in a 2,000-kilowatt-class gas turbine achieving truly CO2-free power generation.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In July 2022, Quad nations of Japan, the US, Australia and India agreed to promote technological development for clean-burning hydrogen and ammonia as fuels at the security grouping's first energy meeting.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] As of 2022, however, significant amounts of NO*x* are produced.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Nitrous oxide may also be a problem as it is a "*greenhouse gas that is known to possess up to 300 times the Global Warming Potential (GWP) of carbon dioxide*".
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia engines or ammonia motors, using ammonia as a working fluid, have been proposed and occasionally used.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The principle is similar to that used in a fireless locomotive, but with ammonia as the working fluid, instead of steam or compressed air.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia engines were used experimentally in the 19th century by Goldsworthy Gurney in the UK and the St.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Charles Streetcar Line in New Orleans in the 1870s and 1880s, and during World War II ammonia was used to power buses in Belgium.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is sometimes proposed as a practical alternative to fossil fuel for internal combustion engines.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] However, ammonia cannot be easily used in existing Otto cycle engines because of its very narrow flammability range.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Despite this, several tests have been run.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Its high octane rating of 120 and low flame temperature allows the use of high compression ratios without a penalty of high NO*x* production.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Since ammonia contains no carbon, its combustion cannot produce carbon dioxide, carbon monoxide, hydrocarbons, or soot.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] At high temperature and in the presence of a suitable catalyst, ammonia decomposes into its constituent elements.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Decomposition of ammonia is a slightly endothermic process requiring 23 kJ/mol (5.5 kcal/mol) of ammonia, and yields hydrogen and nitrogen gas.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Rocket engines have also been fuelled by ammonia.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The Reaction Motors XLR99 rocket engine that powered the X-15 hypersonic research aircraft used liquid ammonia.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Although not as powerful as other fuels, it left no soot in the reusable rocket engine, and its density approximately matches the density of the oxidiser, liquid oxygen, which simplified the aircraft's design.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia is also an attractive alternative to liquid hydrogen as a nuclear-thermal rocket propellant, offering increased thrust (at reduced fuel efficiency).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The company ACWA Power and the city of Neom have announced the construction of a green hydrogen and ammonia plant in 2020.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is used to scrub SO2 from the burning of fossil fuels, and the resulting product is converted to ammonium sulfate for use as fertiliser.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia neutralises the nitrogen oxide (NO*x*) pollutants emitted by diesel engines.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] This technology, called SCR (selective catalytic reduction), relies on a vanadia-based catalyst.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia may be used to mitigate gaseous spills of phosgene.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia, as the vapour released by smelling salts, has found significant use as a respiratory stimulant.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is commonly used in the illegal manufacture of methamphetamine through a Birch reduction.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The Birch method of making methamphetamine is dangerous because the alkali metal and liquid ammonia are both extremely reactive, and the temperature of liquid ammonia makes it susceptible to explosive boiling when reactants are added.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia is used for treatment of cotton materials, giving properties like mercerisation, using alkalis.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In particular, it is used for prewashing of wool.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, ammonia is less dense than atmosphere and has approximately 45–48% of the lifting power of hydrogen or helium.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia has sometimes been used to fill balloons as a lifting gas.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Because of its relatively high boiling point (compared to helium and hydrogen), ammonia could potentially be refrigerated and liquefied aboard an airship to reduce lift and add ballast (and returned to a gas to add lift and reduce ballast).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia has been used to darken quartersawn white oak in Arts & Crafts and Mission-style furniture.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia fumes react with the natural tannins in the wood and cause it to change colour.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is used as an ingredient in various cleaning products, such as Windex (until 2006), in the form of ammonia solution.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The US Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has set a 15-minute exposure limit for gaseous ammonia of 35 ppm by volume in the environmental air and an 8-hour exposure limit of 25 ppm by volume.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Other organisations have varying exposure levels.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] US Navy Standards [US Bureau of Ships 1962] maximum allowable concentrations (MACs): for continuous exposure (60 days) is 25 ppm; for exposure of 1 hour is 400 ppm.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is an irritant and irritation increases with concentration; the permissible exposure limit is 25 ppm, and lethal above 500 ppm by volume.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia vapour has a sharp, irritating, pungent odour that acts as a warning of potentially dangerous exposure.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The average odour threshold is 5 ppm, well below any danger or damage.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Exposure to very high concentrations of gaseous ammonia can result in lung damage and death.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is regulated in the US as a non-flammable gas, but it meets the definition of a material that is toxic by inhalation and requires a hazardous safety permit when transported in quantities greater than 3,500 US gallons (13,000 L; 2,900 imp gal).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The toxicity of ammonia solutions does not usually cause problems for humans and other mammals because they possess metabolic pathways that prevent ammonia from accumulating in the bloodstream.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is converted to carbamoyl phosphate by the enzyme carbamoyl phosphate synthetase and then enters the urea cycle, where it is incorporated into amino acids or excreted as urea.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Fish and amphibians lack this internal detoxification mechanism because they normally eliminate ammonia directly into the surrounding water.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] As a result, they are highly sensitive to elevated environmental concentrations: even dilute levels in the water can impede excretion and lead to toxic accumulation.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] For this reason, ammonia in aquatic environments is classified as *dangerous for the environment*.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Atmospheric ammonia also plays a key role in the formation of fine particulate matter.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is also a constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is present in coking wastewater streams, as a liquid by-product of the production of coke from coal.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In some cases, the ammonia is discharged to the marine environment where it acts as a pollutant.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The Whyalla Steelworks in South Australia is one example of a coke-producing facility that discharges ammonia into marine waters.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia toxicity is believed to be a cause of otherwise unexplained losses in fish hatcheries.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Excess ammonia may accumulate and cause alteration of metabolism or increases in the body pH of the exposed organism.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] At lower concentrations, around 0.05 mg/L, un-ionised ammonia is harmful to fish species and can result in poor growth and feed conversion rates, reduced fecundity and fertility and increase stress and susceptibility to bacterial infections and diseases.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Exposed to excess ammonia, fish may suffer loss of equilibrium, hyper-excitability, increased respiratory activity and oxygen uptake and increased heart rate.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] At concentrations exceeding 2.0 mg/L, ammonia causes gill and tissue damage, extreme lethargy, convulsions, coma, and death.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Experiments have shown that the lethal concentration for a variety of fish species ranges from 0.2 to 2.0 mg/L.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] During winter, when reduced feeds are administered to aquaculture stock, ammonia levels can be higher.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Lower ambient temperatures reduce the rate of algal photosynthesis so less ammonia is removed by any algae present.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Within an aquaculture environment, especially at large scale, there is no fast-acting remedy to elevated ammonia levels.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Prevention rather than correction is recommended to reduce harm to farmed fish and in open water systems, the surrounding environment.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Similar to propane, anhydrous ammonia boils below room temperature when at atmospheric pressure.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] A storage vessel capable of 250 psi (1.7 MPa) is suitable to contain the liquid.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia is used in numerous different industrial applications requiring carbon or stainless steel storage vessels.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia with at least 0.2% by weight water content is not corrosive to carbon steel.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] NH3 carbon steel construction storage tanks with 0.2% by weight or more of water could last more than 50 years in service.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Experts warn that ammonium compounds not be allowed to come in contact with bases (unless in an intended and contained reaction), as dangerous quantities of ammonia gas could be released.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The hazards of ammonia solutions depend on the concentration: 'dilute' ammonia solutions are usually 5–10% by weight (< 5.62 mol/L); 'concentrated' solutions are usually prepared at >25% by weight.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] A 25% (by weight) solution has a density of 0.907 g/cm3, and a solution that has a lower density will be more concentrated.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The European Union classification of ammonia solutions is given in the table.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The ammonia vapour from concentrated ammonia solutions is severely irritating to the eyes and the respiratory tract, and experts warn that these solutions only be handled in a fume hood.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Saturated ('0.880'–see *§ Properties*) solutions can develop a significant pressure inside a closed bottle in warm weather, and experts also warn that the bottle be opened with care.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] This is not usually a problem for 25% ('0.900') solutions.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Experts warn that ammonia solutions not be mixed with halogens, as toxic and/or explosive products are formed.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Anhydrous ammonia is classified as toxic (**T**) and dangerous for the environment (**N**).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The gas is flammable (autoignition temperature: 651 °C) and can form explosive mixtures with air (16–25%).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The permissible exposure limit (PEL) in the United States is 50 ppm (35 mg/m3), while the IDLH concentration is estimated at 300 ppm.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Repeated exposure to ammonia lowers the sensitivity to the smell of the gas: normally the odour is detectable at concentrations of less than 50 ppm, but desensitised individuals may not detect it even at concentrations of 100 ppm.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Anhydrous ammonia corrodes copper- and zinc-containing alloys, which makes brass fittings not appropriate for handling the gas.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Liquid ammonia can also attack rubber and certain plastics.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia reacts violently with the halogens.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Nitrogen triiodide, a primary high explosive, is formed when ammonia comes in contact with iodine.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia causes the explosive polymerisation of ethylene oxide.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] It also forms explosive fulminating compounds with compounds of gold, silver, mercury, germanium or tellurium, and with stibine.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Violent reactions have also been reported with acetaldehyde, hypochlorite solutions, potassium ferricyanide and peroxides.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Ammonia has one of the highest rates of production of any inorganic chemical.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Production is sometimes expressed in terms of "fixed nitrogen".
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Global production was estimated as being 160 million tonnes in 2020 (147 tons of fixed nitrogen).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] China accounted for 26.5% of that, followed by Russia at 11.0%, the United States at 9.5%, and India at 8.3%.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The Haber process, also called the Haber–Bosch process, is the main industrial procedure for the production of ammonia.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] This reaction is exothermic but disfavored in terms of entropy because four equivalents of reactant gases are converted into two equivalents of product gas.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] However, due to the extremely high kinetic barriers to bond cleavage, high pressures and temperatures are needed to drive the reaction forward.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The Haber Process was first created by the German Chemist Fritz Haber, then developed after a few years by Carl Bosch.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The German chemists Fritz Haber and Carl Bosch developed the process in the first decade of the 20th century, and its improved efficiency over existing methods such as the Birkeland–Eyde and Frank–Caro processes was a major advancement in the industrial production of ammonia.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The Haber process can be combined with steam reforming to produce ammonia with just three chemical inputs: water, natural gas, and atmospheric nitrogen.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Both Haber and Bosch were eventually awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry: Haber in 1918 for ammonia synthesis specifically, and Bosch in 1931 for related contributions to high-pressure chemistry.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The electrochemical synthesis of ammonia involves the reductive formation of lithium nitride, which can be protonated to ammonia, given a proton source.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The first use of this chemistry was reported in 1930, where lithium solutions in ethanol were used to produce ammonia at pressures of up to 1000 bar, with ethanol acting as the proton source.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Beyond simply mediating proton transfer to the nitrogen reduction reaction, ethanol has been found to play a multifaceted role, influencing electrolyte transformations and contributing to the formation of the solid electrolyte interphase, which enhances overall reaction efficiency.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In 1994, Tsuneto et al. used lithium electrodeposition in tetrahydrofuran to synthesize ammonia at more moderate pressures with reasonable Faradaic efficiency.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Subsequent studies have further explored the ethanol–tetrahydrofuran system for electrochemical ammonia synthesis.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In 2020, a solvent-agnostic gas diffusion electrode was shown to improve nitrogen transport to the reactive lithium.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] NH3 production rates of up to 30 ± 5 nmol/(s⋅cm2) and Faradaic efficiencies of up to 47.5 ± 4% at ambient temperature and 1 bar pressure were achieved.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In 2021, it was demonstrated that ethanol could be replaced with a tetraalkyl phosphonium salt.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The study observed NH3 production rates of 53 ± 1 nmol/(s⋅cm2) at 69 ± 1% Faradaic efficiency experiments under 0.5 bar hydrogen and 19.5 bar nitrogen partial pressure at ambient temperature.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] Technology based on this electrochemistry is being developed for commercial fertiliser and fuel production.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] In 2022, ammonia was produced via the lithium mediated process in a continuous-flow electrolyzer also demonstrating the hydrogen gas as proton source.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p01] The study synthesised ammonia at 61 ± 1% Faradaic efficiency at a current density of −6 mA/cm2 at 1 bar and room temperature.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] For example, it is required for the formation of amino acids and nucleic acids, fundamental building blocks of life.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Within a cell, glutamate serves this role.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] In the bloodstream, glutamine is a source of ammonia.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonia is both a metabolic waste and a metabolic input throughout the biosphere.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] It is an important source of nitrogen for living systems.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Although atmospheric nitrogen abounds (more than 75%), few living creatures are capable of using atmospheric nitrogen in its diatomic form, N2 gas.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Therefore, nitrogen fixation is required for the synthesis of amino acids, which are the building blocks of protein.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Some plants rely on ammonia and other nitrogenous wastes incorporated into the soil by decaying matter.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Others, such as nitrogen-fixing legumes, benefit from symbiotic relationships with rhizobia bacteria that create ammonia from atmospheric nitrogen.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] In humans, inhaling ammonia in high concentrations can be fatal.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Exposure to ammonia can cause headaches, edema, impaired memory, seizures and coma as it is neurotoxic in nature.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] In certain organisms, ammonia is produced from atmospheric nitrogen by enzymes called nitrogenases.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The overall process is called nitrogen fixation.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Intense effort has been directed toward understanding the mechanism of biological nitrogen fixation.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The scientific interest in this problem is motivated by the unusual structure of the active site of the enzyme, which consists of an Fe7MoS9 ensemble.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonia is also a metabolic product of amino acid deamination catalysed by enzymes such as glutamate dehydrogenase 1.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonia excretion is common in aquatic animals.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] In humans, it is quickly converted to urea (by liver), which is much less toxic, particularly less basic.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] This urea is a major component of the dry weight of urine.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Most reptiles, birds, insects, and snails excrete uric acid solely as nitrogenous waste.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonia plays a role in both normal and abnormal animal physiology.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] It is biosynthesised through normal amino acid metabolism and is toxic in high concentrations.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The liver converts ammonia to urea through a series of reactions known as the urea cycle.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Liver dysfunction, such as that seen in cirrhosis, may lead to elevated amounts of ammonia in the blood (hyperammonemia).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Likewise, defects in the enzymes responsible for the urea cycle, such as ornithine transcarbamylase, lead to hyperammonemia.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Hyperammonemia contributes to the confusion and coma of hepatic encephalopathy, as well as the neurological disease common in people with urea cycle defects and organic acidurias.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonia is important for normal animal acid/base balance.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] After formation of ammonium from glutamine, α-ketoglutarate may be degraded to produce two bicarbonate ions, which are then available as buffers for dietary acids.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonium is excreted in the urine, resulting in net acid loss.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonia may itself diffuse across the renal tubules, combine with a hydrogen ion, and thus allow for further acid excretion.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonium ions are a toxic waste product of metabolism in animals.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] In fish and aquatic invertebrates, it is excreted directly into the water.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] In mammals, sharks, and amphibians, it is converted in the urea cycle to urea, which is less toxic and can be stored more efficiently.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] In birds, reptiles, and terrestrial snails, metabolic ammonium is converted into uric acid, which is solid and can therefore be excreted with minimal water loss.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonia has been detected in the atmospheres of the giant planets Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune, along with other gases such as methane, hydrogen, and helium.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The interior of Saturn may include frozen ammonia crystals.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonia was first detected in interstellar space in 1968, based on microwave emissions from the direction of the galactic core.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] This was the first polyatomic molecule to be so detected.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The sensitivity of the molecule to a broad range of excitations and the ease with which it can be observed in a number of regions has made ammonia one of the most important molecules for studies of molecular clouds.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The relative intensity of the ammonia lines can be used to measure the temperature of the emitting medium.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The following isotopic species of ammonia have been detected: NH3,15NH3, NH2D, NHD2, and ND3.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The detection of triply deuterated ammonia was considered a surprise as deuterium is relatively scarce.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] It is thought that the low-temperature conditions allow this molecule to survive and accumulate.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Since its interstellar discovery, NH3 has proved to be an invaluable spectroscopic tool in the study of the interstellar medium.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] With a large number of transitions sensitive to a wide range of excitation conditions, NH3 has been widely astronomically detected–its detection has been reported in hundreds of journal articles.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Listed below is a sample of journal articles that highlights the range of detectors that have been used to identify ammonia.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The study of interstellar ammonia has been important to a number of areas of research in the last few decades.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Some of these are delineated below and primarily involve using ammonia as an interstellar thermometer.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The interstellar abundance for ammonia has been measured for a variety of environments.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The [NH3]/[H2] ratio has been estimated to range from 10−7 in small dark clouds up to 10−5 in the dense core of the Orion molecular cloud complex.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The rate constant, *k*, of this reaction depends on the temperature of the environment, with a value of $5.2\times 10^{-6}$ at 10 K.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The rate constant was calculated from the formula ⁠ $k=a(T/300)^{B}$ ⁠.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Assuming an NH+4 abundance of $3\times 10^{-7}$ and an electron abundance of 10−7 typical of molecular clouds, the formation will proceed at a rate of 1.6×10−9 cm−3s−1 in a molecular cloud of total density 105 cm−3.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] All other proposed formation reactions have rate constants of between two and 13 orders of magnitude smaller, making their contribution to the abundance of ammonia relatively insignificant.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Assuming H2 densities of 105 and [NH2]/[H2] ratio of 10−7, this reaction proceeds at a rate of 2.2×10−12, more than three orders of magnitude slower than the primary reaction above.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] There are 113 total proposed reactions leading to the destruction of NH3.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Of these, 39 were tabulated in extensive tables of the chemistry among C, N and O compounds.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] These calculations assumed the given rate constants and abundances of [NH3]/[H2] = 10−5, [[H3]+]/[H2] = 2×10−5, [HCO+]/[H2] = 2×10−9, and total densities of *n* = 105, typical of cold, dense, molecular clouds.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Clearly, between these two primary reactions, equation (**1**) is the dominant destruction reaction, with a rate ≈10,000 times faster than equation (**2**).
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] This is due to the relatively high abundance of [H3]+.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Radio observations of NH3 from the Effelsberg 100-m Radio Telescope reveal that the ammonia line is separated into two components–a background ridge and an unresolved core.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The background corresponds well with the locations previously detected CO.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The 25 m Chilbolton telescope in England detected radio signatures of ammonia in H II regions, HNH2O masers, H–H objects, and other objects associated with star formation.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] A comparison of emission line widths indicates that turbulent or systematic velocities do not increase in the central cores of molecular clouds.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Microwave radiation from ammonia was observed in several galactic objects including W3(OH), Orion A, W43, W51, and five sources in the galactic centre.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The high detection rate indicates that this is a common molecule in the interstellar medium and that high-density regions are common in the galaxy.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] VLA observations of NH3 in seven regions with high-velocity gaseous outflows revealed condensations of less than 0.1 pc in L1551, S140, and Cepheus A.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Three individual condensations were detected in Cepheus A, one of them with a highly elongated shape.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] They may play an important role in creating the bipolar outflow in the region.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Extragalactic ammonia was imaged using the VLA in IC 342.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The hot gas has temperatures above 70 K, which was inferred from ammonia line ratios and appears to be closely associated with the innermost portions of the nuclear bar seen in CO.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Based upon temperature and density diagnostics, it is concluded that in general such clumps are probably the sites of massive star formation in an early evolutionary phase prior to the development of an ultracompact HII region.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Absorption at 2.97 micrometres due to solid ammonia was recorded from interstellar grains in the Becklin–Neugebauer Object and probably in NGC 2264-IR as well.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] This detection helped explain the physical shape of previously poorly understood and related ice absorption lines.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] A spectrum of the disk of Jupiter was obtained from the Kuiper Airborne Observatory, covering the 100 to 300 cm−1 spectral range.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Analysis of the spectrum provides information on global mean properties of ammonia gas and an ammonia ice haze.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] A total of 149 dark cloud positions were surveyed for evidence of 'dense cores' by using the (J,K) = (1,1) rotating inversion line of NH3.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] In general, the cores are not spherically shaped, with aspect ratios ranging from 1.1 to 4.4.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] It is also found that cores with stars have broader lines than cores without stars.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonia has been detected in the Draco Nebula and in one or possibly two molecular clouds, which are associated with the high-latitude galactic infrared cirrus.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The finding is significant because they may represent the birthplaces for the Population I metallicity B-type stars in the galactic halo that could have been borne in the galactic disk.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] By balancing and stimulated emission with spontaneous emission, it is possible to construct a relation between excitation temperature and density.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Moreover, since the transitional levels of ammonia can be approximated by a 2-level system at low temperatures, this calculation is fairly simple.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] This premise can be applied to dark clouds, regions suspected of having extremely low temperatures and possible sites for future star formation.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Detections of ammonia in dark clouds show very narrow lines – indicative not only of low temperatures, but also of a low level of inner-cloud turbulence.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Line ratio calculations provide a measurement of cloud temperature that is independent of previous CO observations.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The ammonia observations were consistent with CO measurements of rotation temperatures of ≈10 K.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] With this, densities can be determined, and have been calculated to range between 104 and 105 cm−3 in dark clouds.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Mapping of NH3 gives typical clouds sizes of 0.1 pc and masses near 1 solar mass.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] These cold, dense cores are the sites of future star formation.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ultra-compact HII regions are among the best tracers of high-mass star formation.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] The dense material surrounding UCHII regions is likely primarily molecular.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Since a complete study of massive star formation necessarily involves the cloud from which the star formed, ammonia is an invaluable tool in understanding this surrounding molecular material.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Since this molecular material can be spatially resolved, it is possible to constrain the heating/ionising sources, temperatures, masses, and sizes of the regions.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Doppler-shifted velocity components allow for the separation of distinct regions of molecular gas that can trace outflows and hot cores originating from forming stars.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Ammonia has been detected in external galaxies, and by simultaneously measuring several lines, it is possible to directly measure the gas temperature in these galaxies.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] Line ratios imply that gas temperatures are warm (≈50 K), originating from dense clouds with sizes of tens of parsecs.
[src:bittern-salt/ammonia-p02] This picture is consistent with the picture within our Milky Way galaxy – hot dense molecular cores form around newly forming stars embedded in larger clouds of molecular material on the scale of several hundred parsecs (giant molecular clouds; GMCs).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea were initially classified as bacteria, receiving the name archaebacteria (/ˌɑːrkibækˈtɪəriə/, in the Archaebacteria kingdom), but this term has fallen out of use.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaeal cells have unique properties distinguishing them from Bacteria and Eukaryota, including: cell membranes made of ether-linked lipids; metabolisms such as methanogenesis; and a unique motility structure known as an archaellum.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea are further divided into multiple recognized phyla.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Classification is difficult because most have not been isolated in a laboratory and have been identified only by their gene sequences in environmental samples.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] They have not been observed to produce endospores.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea are often similar to bacteria in size and shape, although a few have very different shapes, such as the flat, square cells of *Haloquadratum walsbyi*.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Despite this, archaea possess genes and several metabolic pathways that are more closely related to those of eukaryotes, notably for the enzymes involved in transcription and translation.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Other aspects of archaeal biochemistry are unique, such as their reliance on ether lipids in their cell membranes, including archaeols.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea use more diverse energy sources than eukaryotes, ranging from organic compounds such as sugars, to ammonia, metal ions or even hydrogen gas.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The salt-tolerant Halobacteria use sunlight as an energy source, and other species of archaea fix carbon (autotrophy), but unlike cyanobacteria, no known species of archaea does both.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea reproduce asexually by binary fission, fragmentation, or budding; unlike bacteria, no known species of Archaea form endospores.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The first observed archaea were extremophiles, living in extreme environments such as hot springs and salt lakes with no other organisms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Improved molecular detection tools led to the discovery of archaea in almost every habitat, including soil, oceans, and marshlands.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea are particularly numerous in the oceans, and the archaea in plankton may be one of the most abundant groups of organisms on the planet.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea are a major part of Earth's life.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] They are part of the microbiota of all organisms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In the human microbiome, they are important in the gut, mouth, and on the skin.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Their morphological, metabolic, and geographical diversity permits them to play multiple ecological roles: carbon fixation; nitrogen cycling; organic compound turnover; and maintaining microbial symbiotic and syntrophic communities, for example.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] As of 2024, only one species of archaea has been found to be parasitic; many are mutualists or commensals, such as the methanogens (methane-producers) that inhabit the gastrointestinal tract in humans and ruminants, where their vast numbers facilitate digestion.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Methanogens are used in biogas production and sewage treatment, while biotechnology exploits enzymes from extremophile archaea that can endure high temperatures and organic solvents.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] For much of the 20th century, prokaryotes were regarded as a single group of organisms and classified based on their biochemistry, morphology and metabolism.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Microbiologists tried to classify microorganisms based on the structures of their cell walls, their shapes, and the substances they consume.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In 1965, Emile Zuckerkandl and Linus Pauling instead proposed using the sequences of the genes in different prokaryotes to work out how they are related to each other.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This phylogenetic approach is the main method used today.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The first archaea to be isolated and grown in pure culture were methane-producing species in the genera Methanobacterium and Methanococcus in the 1930s and 1940s, although at the time, they were classified as bacteria.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea were first classified separately from bacteria in 1977 by Carl Woese and George E.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Fox, based on their ribosomal RNA (rRNA) genes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] (At that time only the methanogens were known).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] They called these groups the *Urkingdoms* of Archaebacteria and Eubacteria, though other researchers treated them as kingdoms or subkingdoms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Woese and Fox gave the first evidence for Archaebacteria as a separate "line of descent": 1. lack of peptidoglycan in their cell walls, 2. two unusual coenzymes, 3. results of 16S ribosomal RNA gene sequencing.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] To emphasize this difference, Woese, Otto Kandler and Mark Wheelis later proposed reclassifying organisms into three then thought to be natural domains known as the three-domain system: the Eukarya, the Bacteria and the Archaea, in what is now known as the Woesian Revolution.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Extreme halophilic and hyperthermophilic microbes were also included in Archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] For a long time, archaea were seen as extremophiles that exist only in extreme habitats such as hot springs and salt lakes, but by the end of the 20th century, archaea had been identified in non-extreme environments as well.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Today, they are known to be a large and diverse group of organisms abundantly distributed throughout nature.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This new appreciation of the importance and ubiquity of archaea came from using polymerase chain reaction (PCR) to detect prokaryotes from environmental samples (such as water or soil) by multiplying their ribosomal genes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This allows the detection and identification of organisms that have not been cultured in the laboratory.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The classification of archaea, and of prokaryotes in general, is a rapidly moving and contentious field.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Current classification systems aim to organize archaea into groups of organisms that share structural features and common ancestors.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These classifications rely heavily on the use of the sequence of ribosomal RNA genes to reveal relationships among organisms (molecular phylogenetics).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Most of the culturable and well-investigated species of archaea are members of two main kingdoms, the Methanobacteriati and the Thermoproteati (formerly TACK).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Other groups have been tentatively created, such as the peculiar species *Nanoarchaeum equitans* – discovered in 2003 and assigned its own phylum, the Nanoarchaeota (reassigned to Nanobdellota in 2023).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] A new phylum "Korarchaeota" (now Thermoproteota) has also been proposed, containing a small group of unusual thermophilic species sharing features of both the main phyla.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Other detected species of archaea are only distantly related to any of these groups, such as the Archaeal Richmond Mine acidophilic nanoorganisms (ARMAN, comprising Micrarchaeota and Parvarchaeota), which were discovered in 2006 and are some of the smallest organisms known.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] A superphylum – "TACK" (now kingdom Thermoproteati) – which includes the Thaumarchaeota (now Nitrososphaerota), "Augarchaeota", Crenarchaeota (now Thermoproteota), and "Korarchaeota" (now Thermoproteota) was proposed in 2011 to be related to the origin of eukaryotes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In 2017, the newly discovered and newly named "Asgard" (now kingdom Promethearchaeati) superphylum was proposed to be more closely related to the original eukaryote and a sister group to Thermoproteati / "TACK".
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In 2013, the superphylum "DPANN" (now kingdom Nanobdellati) was proposed to group "Nanoarchaeota", "Nanohaloarchaeota", Archaeal Richmond Mine acidophilic nanoorganisms (ARMAN, comprising "Micrarchaeota" and "Parvarchaeota"), and other similar archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This archaeal superphylum encompasses at least 10 different lineages and includes organisms with extremely small cell and genome sizes and limited metabolic capabilities.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Therefore, Nanobdellati/"DPANN" may include members obligately dependent on symbiotic interactions, and may even include novel parasites.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] However, other phylogenetic analyses found that Nanobdellati/"DPANN" does not form a monophyletic group, and that the apparent grouping is caused by long branch attraction (LBA), suggesting that all these lineages belong to Methanobacteriati.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The classification of archaea into species is also controversial.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Ernst Mayr's species definition – a reproductively isolated group of interbreeding organisms - does not apply, as archaea reproduce only asexually.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea show high levels of horizontal gene transfer between lineages.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Some researchers suggest that individuals can be grouped into species-like populations given highly similar genomes and infrequent gene transfer to/from cells with less-related genomes, as in the genus *Ferroplasma*.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] On the other hand, studies in *Halorubrum* found significant genetic transfer to/from less-related populations, limiting the criterion's applicability.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Some researchers question whether such species designations have practical meaning.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Current knowledge on genetic diversity in archaeans is fragmentary, so the total number of species cannot be estimated with any accuracy.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Estimates of the number of phyla range from 18 to 23, of which only 8 have representatives that have been cultured and studied directly.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Many of these hypothesized groups are known from a single rRNA sequence, so the level of diversity remains obscure.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This situation is also seen in the Bacteria; many uncultured microbes present similar issues with characterization.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The age of the Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Scientific evidence suggests that life began on Earth at least 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The earliest evidence for life on Earth is graphite found to be biogenic in 3.7-billion-year-old metasedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland and microbial mat fossils found in 3.48-billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In 2015, possible remains of biotic matter were found in 4.1-billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Although probable prokaryotic cell fossils date to almost 3.5 billion years ago, most prokaryotes do not have distinctive morphologies, and fossil shapes cannot be used to identify them as archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Instead, chemical fossils of unique lipids are more informative because such compounds do not occur in other organisms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Some publications suggest that archaeal or eukaryotic lipid remains are present in shales dating from 2.7 billion years ago, though such data have since been questioned.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These lipids have also been detected in even older rocks from west Greenland.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The oldest such traces come from the Isua district, which includes Earth's oldest known sediments, formed 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The archaeal lineage may be the most ancient that exists on Earth.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Woese argued that the bacteria, archaea, and eukaryotes represent separate lines of descent that diverged early on from an ancestral colony of organisms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] One possibility is that this occurred before the evolution of cells, when the lack of a typical cell membrane allowed unrestricted lateral gene transfer, and that the common ancestors of the three domains arose by fixation of specific subsets of genes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] It is possible that the last common ancestor of bacteria and archaea was a thermophile, which raises the possibility that lower temperatures are "extreme environments" for archaea, and organisms that live in cooler environments appeared only later.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Since archaea and bacteria are no more related to each other than they are to eukaryotes, the term *prokaryote* may suggest a false similarity between them.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] However, structural and functional similarities between lineages often occur because of shared ancestral traits or evolutionary convergence.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These similarities are known as a *grade*, and prokaryotes are best thought of as a grade of life, characterized by such features as an absence of membrane-bound organelles.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The following table compares some major characteristics of the three domains, to illustrate their similarities and differences.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea were split off as a third domain because of the large differences in their ribosomal RNA structure.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The particular molecule 16S rRNA is key to the production of proteins in all organisms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Because this function is so central to life, organisms with mutations in their 16S rRNA are unlikely to survive, leading to great (but not absolute) stability in the structure of this polynucleotide over generations.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] 16S rRNA is large enough to show organism-specific variations, but still small enough to be compared quickly.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In 1977, Carl Woese, a microbiologist studying the genetic sequences of organisms, developed a new comparison method that involved splitting the RNA into fragments that could be sorted and compared with other fragments from other organisms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The more similar the patterns between species, the more closely they are related.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Woese used his new rRNA comparison method to categorize and contrast different organisms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] He compared a variety of species and happened upon a group of methanogens with rRNA vastly different from any known prokaryotes or eukaryotes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These methanogens were much more similar to each other than to other organisms, leading Woese to propose the new domain of Archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] His experiments showed that the archaea were genetically more similar to eukaryotes than prokaryotes, even though they were more similar to prokaryotes in structure.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This led to the conclusion that Archaea and Eukarya shared a common ancestor more recent than Eukarya and Bacteria.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The development of the nucleus occurred after the split between Bacteria and this common ancestor.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] One property unique to archaea is the abundant use of ether-linked lipids in their cell membranes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Ether linkages are more chemically stable than the ester linkages found in bacteria and eukarya, which may be a contributing factor to the ability of many archaea to survive in extreme environments that place heavy stress on cell membranes, such as extreme heat and salinity.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Comparative analysis of archaeal genomes has also identified several molecular conserved signature indels and signature proteins uniquely present in either all archaea or different main groups within archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Another unique feature of archaea, found in no other organisms, is methanogenesis (the metabolic production of methane).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Methanogenic archaea play a pivotal role in ecosystems with organisms that derive energy from oxidation of methane, many of which are bacteria, as they are often a major source of methane in such environments and can play a role as primary producers.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Methanogens also play a critical role in the carbon cycle, breaking down organic carbon into methane, which is also a major greenhouse gas.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This difference in the biochemical structure of Bacteria and Archaea has been explained by researchers through evolutionary processes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] It is theorized that both domains originated at deep sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] At least twice, microbes evolved lipid biosynthesis and cell wall biochemistry.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] It has been suggested that the last universal common ancestor was a non-free-living organism.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] It may have had a permeable membrane composed of bacterial simple chain amphiphiles (fatty acids), including archaeal simple chain amphiphiles (isoprenoids).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These stabilize fatty acid membranes in seawater; this property may have driven the divergence of bacterial and archaeal membranes, "with the later biosynthesis of phospholipids giving rise to the unique G1P and G3P headgroups of archaea and bacteria respectively.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] If so, the properties conferred by membrane isoprenoids place the lipid divide as early as the origin of life".
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The relationships among the three domains are of central importance for understanding the origin of life.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Most of the metabolic pathways, which are the object of the majority of an organism's genes, are common between Archaea and Bacteria, while most genes involved in gene expression are common between Archaea and Eukarya.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Within prokaryotes, archaeal cell structure is most similar to that of Gram-positive bacteria, largely because both have a single lipid bilayer and usually contain a thick sacculus (exoskeleton) of varying chemical composition.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In some phylogenetic trees based upon different gene / protein sequences of prokaryotic homologs, the archaeal homologs are more closely related to those of gram-positive bacteria.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea and gram-positive bacteria also share conserved indels in a number of important proteins, such as Hsp70 and glutamine synthetase I; but the phylogeny of these genes was interpreted to reveal inter-domain gene transfer, and might not reflect the organismal relationship(s).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] It has been proposed that the archaea evolved from Gram-positive bacteria in response to antibiotic selection pressure.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This is suggested by the observation that archaea are resistant to a wide variety of antibiotics that are produced primarily by Gram-positive bacteria, and that these antibiotics act primarily on the genes that distinguish archaea from bacteria.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The proposal is that the selective pressure towards resistance generated by the gram-positive antibiotics was eventually sufficient to cause extensive changes in many of the antibiotics' target genes, and that these strains represented the common ancestors of present-day Archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This proposal is also supported by other work investigating protein structural relationships and studies that suggest that gram-positive bacteria may constitute the earliest branching lineages within the prokaryotes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The evolutionary relationship between archaea and eukaryotes remains unclear.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Aside from the similarities in cell structure and function that are discussed below, many genetic trees group the two.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The standard hypothesis states that the ancestor of the eukaryotes diverged early from the Archaea, and that eukaryotes arose through symbiogenesis, the fusion of an archaean and a eubacterium, which formed the mitochondria; this hypothesis explains the genetic similarities between the groups.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The eocyte hypothesis instead posits that Eukaryota emerged relatively late from the Archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] A lineage of archaea discovered in 2015, *Lokiarchaeum* (of the proposed new phylum "Lokiarchaeota"), named for a hydrothermal vent called Loki's Castle in the Arctic Ocean, was found to be the most closely related to eukaryotes known at that time.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] It has been called a transitional organism between prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Several sister phyla of "Lokiarchaeota" have since been found ("Thorarchaeota", "Odinarchaeota", "Heimdallarchaeota"), all together comprising a newly proposed supergroup "Asgard".
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea range from 0.1 micrometers (μm) to over 15 μm in diameter, and commonly occur as spheres, rods, spirals or plates.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Morphologies in the Thermoproteota also include irregularly shaped lobed cells in *Sulfolobus*, needle-like filaments that are less than half a micrometer in diameter in *Thermofilum*, and almost perfectly rectangular rods in *Thermoproteus* and *Pyrobaculum*.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea in the genus *Haloquadratum* such as *Haloquadratum walsbyi* are flat, square specimens that live in hypersaline pools.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These unusual shapes are probably maintained by both their cell walls and a prokaryotic cytoskeleton.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Proteins related to the cytoskeleton components of other organisms exist in archaea, and filaments form within their cells, but in contrast with other organisms, these cellular structures are poorly understood.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In *Thermoplasma* and *Ferroplasma* the lack of a cell wall means that the cells have irregular shapes, and can resemble amoebae.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Some species form aggregates or filaments of cells up to 200 μm long.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These organisms can be prominent in biofilms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Notably, aggregates of *Thermococcus coalescens* cells fuse together in culture, forming single giant cells.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea in the genus *Pyrodictium* produce an elaborate multicell colony involving arrays of long, thin hollow tubes called *cannulae* that stick out from the cells' surfaces and connect them into a dense bush-like agglomeration.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The function of these cannulae is not settled, but they may allow communication or nutrient exchange with neighbors.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Multi-species colonies exist, such as the "string-of-pearls" community that was discovered in 2001 in a German swamp.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Round whitish colonies of a novel Methanobacteriati species are spaced along thin filaments that can range up to 15 centimetres (5.9 in) long; these filaments are made of a particular bacteria species.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea and bacteria have generally similar cell structure, but cell composition and organization set the archaea apart.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Like bacteria, archaea lack interior membranes and organelles.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Like bacteria, the cell membranes of archaea are usually bounded by a cell wall and they swim using one or more flagella.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Structurally, archaea are most similar to gram-positive bacteria.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Most have a single plasma membrane and cell wall, and lack a periplasmic space; the exception to this general rule is *Ignicoccus*, which possess a particularly large periplasm that contains membrane-bound vesicles and is enclosed by an outer membrane.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Most archaea (but not *Thermoplasma* and *Ferroplasma*) possess a cell wall.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In most archaea, the wall is assembled from surface-layer proteins, which form an S-layer.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] An S-layer is a rigid array of protein molecules that cover the outside of the cell (like chain mail).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This layer provides both chemical and physical protection, and can prevent macromolecules from contacting the cell membrane.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Unlike bacteria, archaea lack peptidoglycan in their cell walls.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaeal flagella are known as archaella, that operate like bacterial flagella – their long stalks are driven by rotatory motors at the base.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These motors are powered by a proton gradient across the membrane, but archaella are notably different in composition and development.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The two types of flagella evolved from different ancestors.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The bacterial flagellum shares a common ancestor with the type III secretion system, while archaeal flagella appear to have evolved from bacterial type IV pili.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In contrast with the bacterial flagellum, which is hollow and assembled by subunits moving up the central pore to the tip of the flagella, archaeal flagella are synthesized by adding subunits at the base.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaeal membranes are made of different molecules from those in bacterial and eukaryotic membranes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In all organisms, cell membranes are made of molecules known as phospholipids.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These molecules possess both a polar part that dissolves in water (the phosphate "head"), and a "greasy" non-polar part that does not (the lipid tail).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These dissimilar parts are connected by a glycerol moiety.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In water, phospholipids cluster, with the heads facing the water and the tails facing away from it.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The major structure in cell membranes is a double layer of these phospholipids, which is called a lipid bilayer.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea exhibit a great variety of chemical reactions in their metabolism and use many sources of energy.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These reactions are classified into nutritional groups, depending on energy and carbon sources.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Some archaea obtain energy from inorganic compounds such as sulfur or ammonia (they are chemotrophs).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These include nitrifiers, methanogens and anaerobic methane oxidisers.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In these reactions, one compound passes electrons to another (in a redox reaction), releasing energy to fuel the cell's activities.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] One compound acts as an electron donor and one as an electron acceptor.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The energy released is used to generate adenosine triphosphate (ATP) through chemiosmosis, the same basic process that happens in the mitochondrion of eukaryotic cells.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Other groups of archaea use sunlight as a source of energy (they are phototrophs), but oxygen–generating photosynthesis does not occur in any of these organisms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Many basic metabolic pathways are shared among all forms of life; for example, archaea use a modified form of glycolysis (the Entner–Doudoroff pathway) and either a complete or partial citric acid cycle.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These similarities to other organisms probably reflect both early origins in the history of life and their high level of efficiency.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Some Methanobacteriati are methanogens (archaea that produce methane as a result of metabolism) living in anaerobic environments, such as swamps.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This form of metabolism evolved early, and it is even possible that the first free-living organism was a methanogen.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] A common reaction involves the use of carbon dioxide as an electron acceptor to oxidize hydrogen.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Methanogenesis involves a range of coenzymes that are unique to these archaea, such as coenzyme M and methanofuran.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Other organic compounds such as alcohols, acetic acid or formic acid are used as alternative electron acceptors by methanogens.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These reactions are common in gut-dwelling archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Acetic acid is also broken down into methane and carbon dioxide directly, by *acetotrophic* archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These acetotrophs are archaea in the order Methanosarcinales, and are a major part of the communities of microorganisms that produce biogas.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Other archaea use CO 2 in the atmosphere as a source of carbon, in a process called carbon fixation (they are autotrophs).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This process involves either a highly modified form of the Calvin cycle or another metabolic pathway called the 3-hydroxypropionate / 4-hydroxybutyrate cycle.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The Thermoproteota also use the reverse Krebs cycle while the Methanobacteriati also use the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Carbon fixation is powered by inorganic energy sources.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] No known archaea carry out photosynthesis.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaeal energy sources are extremely diverse, and range from the oxidation of ammonia by the Nitrosopumilales to the oxidation of hydrogen sulfide or elemental sulfur by species of *Sulfolobus*, using either oxygen or metal ions as electron acceptors.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Phototrophic archaea use light to produce chemical energy in the form of ATP.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In the Halobacteria, light-activated ion pumps like bacteriorhodopsin and halorhodopsin generate ion gradients by pumping ions out of and into the cell across the plasma membrane.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The energy stored in these electrochemical gradients is then converted into ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This process is a form of photophosphorylation.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The ability of these light-driven pumps to move ions across membranes depends on light-driven changes in the structure of a retinol cofactor buried in the center of the protein.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea usually have a single circular chromosome, but many euryarchaea have been shown to bear multiple copies of this chromosome.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The largest known archaeal genome as of 2002 was 5,751,492 base pairs in *Methanosarcina acetivorans*.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The tiny 490,885 base-pair genome of *Nanoarchaeum equitans* is one-tenth of this size and the smallest archaeal genome known; it is estimated to contain only 537 protein-encoding genes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Smaller independent pieces of DNA, called *plasmids*, are also found in archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Plasmids may be transferred between cells by physical contact, in a process that may be similar to bacterial conjugation.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea are genetically distinct from bacteria and eukaryotes, with up to 15% of the proteins encoded by any one archaeal genome being unique to the domain, although most of these unique genes have no known function.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Of the remainder of the unique proteins that have an identified function, most belong to the Methanobacteriati and are involved in methanogenesis.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The proteins that archaea, bacteria and eukaryotes share form a common core of cell function, relating mostly to transcription, translation, and nucleotide metabolism.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Other characteristic archaeal features are the organization of genes of related function – such as enzymes that catalyze steps in the same metabolic pathway into novel operons, and large differences in tRNA genes and their aminoacyl tRNA synthetases.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Transcription in archaea more closely resembles eukaryotic than bacterial transcription, with the archaeal RNA polymerase being very close to its equivalent in eukaryotes, while archaeal translation shows signs of both bacterial and eukaryotic equivalents.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Post-transcriptional modification is simpler than in eukaryotes, since most archaeal genes lack introns, although there are many introns in their transfer RNA and ribosomal RNA genes, and introns may occur in a few protein-encoding genes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] When the hyperthermophilic archaea *Sulfolobus solfataricus* and *Sulfolobus acidocaldarius* are exposed to DNA-damaging UV irradiation or to the agents bleomycin or mitomycin C, species-specific cellular aggregation is induced.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Aggregation in *S. solfataricus* could not be induced by other physical stressors, such as pH or temperature shift, suggesting that aggregation is induced specifically by DNA damage.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Ajon et al. showed that UV-induced cellular aggregation mediates chromosomal marker exchange with high frequency in *S. acidocaldarius*.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Recombination rates exceeded those of uninduced cultures by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Frols et al. and Ajon et al. hypothesized that cellular aggregation enhances species-specific DNA transfer between *Sulfolobus* cells in order to provide increased repair of damaged DNA by means of homologous recombination.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This response may be a primitive form of sexual interaction similar to the more well-studied bacterial transformation systems that are also associated with species-specific DNA transfer between cells leading to homologous recombinational repair of DNA damage.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea are the target of a number of viruses in a diverse virosphere distinct from bacterial and eukaryotic viruses.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] They have been organized into 15–18 DNA-based families so far, but multiple species remain un-isolated and await classification.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These families can be informally divided into two groups: archaea-specific and cosmopolitan.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaeal-specific viruses target only archaean species and currently include 12 families.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Numerous unique, previously unidentified viral structures have been observed in this group, including: bottle-shaped, spindle-shaped, coil-shaped, and droplet-shaped viruses.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] While the reproductive cycles and genomic mechanisms of archaea-specific species may be similar to other viruses, they bear unique characteristics that were specifically developed due to the morphology of host cells they infect.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Their virus release mechanisms differ from that of other phages.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Bacteriophages generally undergo either lytic pathways, lysogenic pathways, or (rarely) a mix of the two.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Most archaea-specific viral strains maintain a stable, somewhat lysogenic, relationship with their hosts – appearing as a chronic infection.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This involves the gradual, and continuous, production and release of virions without killing the host cell.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Prangishyili (2013) noted that it has been hypothesized that tailed archaeal phages originated from bacteriophages capable of infecting haloarchaeal species.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] If the hypothesis is correct, it can be concluded that other double-stranded DNA viruses that make up the rest of the archaea-specific group are their own unique group in the global viral community.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] (2018) states that the high levels of horizontal gene transfer, rapid mutation rates in viral genomes, and lack of universal gene sequences have led researchers to perceive the evolutionary pathway of archaeal viruses as a network.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The lack of similarities among phylogenetic markers in this network and the global virosphere, as well as external linkages to non-viral elements, may suggest that some species of archaea specific viruses evolved from non-viral mobile genetic elements (MGE).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These viruses have been studied in most detail in thermophilics, particularly the orders Sulfolobales and Thermoproteales.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Two groups of single-stranded DNA viruses that infect archaea have been recently isolated.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] One group is exemplified by the *Halorubrum pleomorphic virus 1* (*Pleolipoviridae*) infecting halophilic archaea, and the other one by the *Aeropyrum coil-shaped virus* (*Spiraviridae*) infecting a hyperthermophilic (optimal growth at 90–95 °C) host.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Notably, the latter virus has the largest currently reported ssDNA genome.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Defenses against these viruses may involve RNA interference from repetitive DNA sequences that are related to the genes of the viruses.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea reproduce asexually by binary or multiple fission, fragmentation, or budding; mitosis and meiosis do not occur, so if a species of archaea exists in more than one form, all have the same genetic material.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Cell division is controlled in a cell cycle; after the cell's chromosome is replicated and the two daughter chromosomes separate, the cell divides.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In the genus *Sulfolobus*, the cycle has characteristics that are similar to both bacterial and eukaryotic systems.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] The chromosomes replicate from multiple starting points (origins of replication) using DNA polymerases that resemble the equivalent eukaryotic enzymes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In Methanobacteriati the cell division protein FtsZ, which forms a contracting ring around the cell, and the components of the septum that is constructed across the center of the cell, are similar to their bacterial equivalents.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] In cren- and thaumarchaea, the cell division machinery Cdv fulfills a similar role.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] This machinery is related to the eukaryotic ESCRT-III machinery which, while best known for its role in cell sorting, also has been seen to fulfill a role in separation between divided cell, suggesting an ancestral role in cell division.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Both bacteria and eukaryotes, but not archaea, make spores.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Quorum sensing was originally thought to not exist in Archaea, but recent studies have shown evidence of some species being able to perform cross-talk through quorum sensing.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Other studies have shown syntrophic interactions between archaea and bacteria during biofilm growth.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Although research is limited in archaeal quorum sensing, some studies have uncovered LuxR proteins in archaeal species, displaying similarities with bacteria LuxR, and ultimately allowing for the detection of small molecules that are used in high density communication.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Similarly to bacteria, Archaea LuxR solos have shown to bind to AHLs (lactones) and non-AHLs ligans, which is a large part in performing intraspecies, interspecies, and interkingdom communication through quorum sensing.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Archaea are known to form biofilms, a common strategy among microorganisms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Quorum sensing is thought to play a role in Archaeal biofilm formation, but less is known about Archaeal quorum sensing than Bacterial quorum sensing.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Some Archaea have been observed to form biofilms when the pH is a specific value, without necessarily relying on quorum sensing for instance.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] These biofilms are sessile communities of micro-organisms (they can contain multiple different species) that produce extracellular polymeric substances, which are used to create a matrix, within which the micro-organisms can grow.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Biofilms are beneficial as they: protect organisms from abiotic stresses; facilitate horizontal gene transfer; and enable syntropy to take place.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Biofilm formation has a number of stages: attachment; micro-colony formation; maturation; and dispersal.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] During the attachment phase the Archaea are reversibly attached to a surface by type-4 pili and archaella.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Some Archaea possess other structures involved in attachment such as hami; fimbriae; or cannulae.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] During the micro colony phase, the extracellular polymeric substance matrix is produced, and numerous archaea have been observed to produce pills and nanowires between cells.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] During the maturation phase the matrix takes on a sophisticated architecture, such as including pathways for waste to exit the biofilms.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Different archaea have been observed to produce biofilms with different architectures.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p01] Finally, dispersal can take place, where cells begin to leave the biofilm, this process has been observed in Archaea but the mechanisms behind it are not understood.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Archaea exist in a broad range of habitats, are recognized as a major part of global ecosystems, and may represent about 20% of microbial cells in the oceans as well as a large number of cells in sea floor sediment.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] However, the first-discovered archaeans were extremophiles.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Indeed, some archaea survive high temperatures, often above 100 °C (212 °F), as found in geysers, black smokers, and oil wells.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Other common habitats include very cold habitats and highly saline, acidic, or alkaline water, but archaea include mesophiles that grow in mild conditions, in swamps and marshland, sewage, the oceans, the intestinal tract of animals, and soils.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Similar to PGPR, Archaea are considered a source of plant growth promotion as well.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Extremophile archaea are members of four main physiological groups.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] These are the halophiles, thermophiles, alkaliphiles, and acidophiles.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] These groups are not comprehensive or phylum-specific, nor are they mutually exclusive, since some archaea belong to several groups.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Nonetheless, they are a useful starting point for classification.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Halophiles, including the genus *Halobacterium*, live in extremely saline environments such as salt lakes and outnumber their bacterial counterparts at salinities greater than 20–25%.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Thermophiles grow best at temperatures above 45 °C (113 °F), in places such as hot springs; *hyperthermophilic* archaea grow optimally at temperatures greater than 80 °C (176 °F).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] The archaeal *Methanopyrus kandleri* Strain 116 can even reproduce at 122 °C (252 °F), the highest recorded temperature of any organism.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Other archaea exist in very acidic or alkaline conditions.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] For example, one of the most extreme archaean acidophiles is *Picrophilus torridus*, which grows at pH 0, which is equivalent to thriving in 1.2 molar sulfuric acid.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] This resistance to extreme environments has made archaea the focus of speculation about the possible properties of extraterrestrial life.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Some extremophile habitats are not dissimilar to those on Mars, leading to the suggestion that viable microbes could be transferred between planets in meteorites.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Recently, several studies have shown that archaea exist not only in mesophilic and thermophilic environments but are also present, sometimes in high numbers, at low temperatures as well.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] For example, archaea are common in cold oceanic environments such as polar seas.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Even more significant are the large numbers of archaea found throughout the world's oceans in non-extreme habitats among the plankton community (as part of the picoplankton).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Although these archaea can be present in extremely high numbers (up to 40% of the microbial biomass), almost none of these species have been isolated and studied in pure culture.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Consequently, our understanding of the role of archaea in ocean ecology is rudimentary, so their full influence on global biogeochemical cycles remains largely unexplored.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Some marine Thermoproteota are capable of nitrification, suggesting these organisms may affect the oceanic nitrogen cycle, although these oceanic Thermoproteota may also use other sources of energy.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Vast numbers of archaea are also found in the sediments that cover the sea floor, with these organisms making up at least 12.8%, and in many places, the majority of living cells at depths over 1 meter below the ocean bottom.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Archaea recycle elements such as carbon, nitrogen, and sulfur through their various habitats.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Archaea carry out many steps in the nitrogen cycle.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] This includes both reactions that remove nitrogen from ecosystems (such as nitrate-based respiration and denitrification) as well as processes that introduce nitrogen (such as nitrate assimilation and nitrogen fixation).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Researchers recently discovered archaeal involvement in ammonia oxidation reactions.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] These reactions are particularly important in the oceans.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] The archaea also appear crucial for ammonia oxidation in soils.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] They produce nitrite, which other microbes then oxidize to nitrate.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Plants and other organisms consume the latter.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] In the carbon cycle, methanogen archaea remove hydrogen and play an important role in the decay of organic matter by the populations of microorganisms that act as decomposers in anaerobic ecosystems, such as sediments, marshes, and sewage-treatment works.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] The well-characterized interactions between archaea and other organisms are either mutual or commensal.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Mutualism is an interaction between individuals of different species that results in positive (beneficial) effects on per capita reproduction and/or survival of the interacting populations.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] One well-understood example of mutualism is the interaction between protozoa and methanogenic archaea in the digestive tracts of animals that digest cellulose, such as ruminants and termites.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] In these anaerobic environments, protozoa break down plant cellulose to obtain energy.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] This process releases hydrogen as a waste product, but high levels of hydrogen reduce energy production.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] When methanogens convert hydrogen to methane, protozoa benefit from more energy.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] In anaerobic protozoa, such as *Plagiopyla frontata*, *Trimyema*, *Heterometopus* and *Metopus contortus*, archaea reside inside the protozoa and consume hydrogen produced in their hydrogenosomes.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Archaea associate with larger organisms, too.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] For example, the marine archaean *Cenarchaeum symbiosum* is an endosymbiont of the sponge *Axinella mexicana*.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Some archaea are commensals, benefiting from an association without helping or harming the other organism.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] For example, the methanogen *Methanobrevibacter smithii* is by far the most common archaean in the human flora, making up about one in ten of the prokaryotes in the human gut.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] In termites and in humans, these methanogens may in fact be mutualists, interacting with other microbes in the gut to aid digestion.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Archaean communities associate with a range of other organisms, such as on the surface of corals, and in the region of soil that surrounds plant roots (the rhizosphere).
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Although Archaea do not have a historical reputation of being pathogens, Archaea are often found with similar genomes to more common pathogens like *E. coli,* showing metabolic links and evolutionary history with today's pathogens.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Archaea have been inconsistently detected in clinical studies because of the lack of categorization of Archaea into more specific species.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] The reduced genome of *Candidatus* Sukunaarchaeum mirabile suggests it is a specialized parasite highly dependant on its dinoflagellate host.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Extremophile archaea, particularly those resistant either to heat or to extremes of acidity and alkalinity, are a source of enzymes that function under these harsh conditions.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] For example, thermostable DNA polymerases, such as the Pfu DNA polymerase from *Pyrococcus furiosus*, revolutionized molecular biology by allowing the polymerase chain reaction to be used in research as a simple and rapid technique for cloning DNA.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] In industry, amylases, galactosidases and pullulanases in other species of *Pyrococcus* that function at over 100 °C (212 °F) allow food processing at high temperatures, such as the production of low lactose milk and whey.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Enzymes from these thermophilic archaea also tend to be very stable in organic solvents, allowing their use in environmentally friendly processes in green chemistry that synthesize organic compounds.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] This stability makes them easier to use in structural biology.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Consequently, the counterparts of bacterial or eukaryotic enzymes from extremophile archaea are often used in structural studies.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] In contrast with the range of applications of archaean enzymes, the use of the organisms themselves in biotechnology is less developed.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Methanogenic archaea are a vital part of sewage treatment, since they are part of the community of microorganisms that carry out anaerobic digestion and produce biogas.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] In mineral processing, acidophilic archaea display promise for the extraction of metals from ores, including gold, cobalt and copper.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] Archaea host a new class of potentially useful antibiotics.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] A few of these archaeocins have been characterized, but hundreds more are believed to exist, especially within Halobacteria and *Sulfolobus*.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] These compounds differ in structure from bacterial antibiotics, so they may have novel modes of action.
[src:bittern-salt/archaea-p02] In addition, they may allow the creation of new selectable markers for use in archaeal molecular biology.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Both of them are part of the unique traditional methods of producing sea salt for culinary use among the Visayan people of the central Philippine islands.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] They differ in taste from salt obtained through traditional drying beds or modern methods.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] *Asín tibuók* has a sharp, slightly alkaline taste with smoky and fruity undertones, while *túltul* has an innate savory flavor.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] They are characteristically finely textured with small granules.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] They are consumed by grating a light dusting over food.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] The tradition of making *asín tibuók* and *túltul* is nearly extinct due to the difficulty and length of time it takes to manufacture them, the passing of the salt iodization (ASIN) law in 1995, as well as competition with modern imported salts.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] They are only barely preserved in Bohol, Capiz, and Guimaras.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] *Asín tibuók* is listed in the Ark of Taste international catalogue of endangered heritage foods by the Slow Food organization.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Similar salt-making traditions also exist in Guimaras island and the neighboring province of Capiz in Panay Island.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] In Guimaras, it is known as *túltul* or *tul-tul*, meaning "lump"; while in Capiz, it is known as *dukdok*, meaning "pounded" or "pulverized".
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Both names are in the Hiligaynon language of the Ilonggo people.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] The method of production varies slightly between the Boholano *asín tibuók* and the Ilonggo *túltul* or *dúkdok*.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Both methods can only be done for six months of the year, from December to May, due to the fluctuations in seawater salinity during the rainy seasons.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Boholano *asín tibuók* is made by soaking coconut husks for at least three months in special pits continually filled with seawater during the tides.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] They are then cut into small pieces and dried for a few days.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] They are burned in a pile until reduced completely to ash.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] The ashes (called *gasang*) are gathered into a funnel-shaped bamboo filtering device.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Seawater is poured into the ash, allowing the water to leach out the salt from the ashes.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] The brine (known as *tasik*) is collected into a hollowed-out coconut trunk beneath the funnels.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] The *tasik* is poured into special clay pots and hung in walls in a special furnace.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] These are boiled for a few hours in the furnace, continually replenishing the pots with more *tasik* once some evaporate.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Eventually, the pots will crack, revealing the solidified mass of salt.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] The salt mass will be initially very hot, and it usually takes a few hours before it is cool enough to be handled.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] They are sold along with the broken domed pots which has given them the nickname "the dinosaur egg" in international markets due to their appearance.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Ilonggo *túltul*, *duldul*, or *dukdok* is made by gathering driftwood (*rorok* or *dagsa*) and other washed-up plant matter (twigs, reeds, coconut husks, bamboo stems, etc.) from the beach.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] These are burned completely into ash for about a week.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] The ash is then gathered into cylindrical woven bamboo containers known as *kaing*.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] The *kaing* are placed on bamboo platforms and a container is placed underneath.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Seawater is poured through the ash and caught on these containers.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] The brine is then strained and transferred into other containers where it is mixed with *gatâ* (coconut milk).
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] These are poured into molds (*hurnohan*) and boiled over an outdoor stove (*kalán*).
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] More of the liquid is continually poured into the molds as they evaporate until nothing but a solid mass of salt remains.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] These brick-like lumps (known as *bareta*) are then packaged and sold.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Salt-makers (*asinderos*) were once important professions in Philippine society, but the craft is nearly extinct in modern times.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Part of this is due to the time-consuming traditional methods of producing salt and the hard work that goes with it.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Artisanal salt-makers can not compete with the cheap imported salt prevalent today in the Philippines.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] 8172, the Act for Salt Iodization Nationwide (ASIN), in 1995 also placed further stress on local salt-makers, forcing many to give up the industry altogether.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Both *asín tibuok* and *túltul* are only made by a few families today.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] They are commonly sold to tourists and to gourmet restaurants that feature Filipino cuisine.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Due to their rarity, they are more expensive than regular salt.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] Demand for *asín tibuok* and *túltul* frequently exceeds supply.
[src:bittern-salt/asin-tibuok] The production of *asín tibuok* is also dependent on the availability of the raw materials, particularly coconut husks.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Bittern is commonly formed in salt ponds where the evaporation of water prompts the precipitation of halite.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] These salt ponds can be part of a salt-producing industrial facility, or they can be used as a waste storage location for brines produced in desalination processes.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Bittern is a source of many useful salts.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] It is used as a natural source of Mg2+, and it can be used as a coagulant both in the production of tofu and in the treatment of industrial wastewater.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Bittern has been extracted for a long time, at least several centuries.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] The Dutch chemist Petrus Jacobus Kipp (1808–1864) experimented with saturated solutions of bittern.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] The term for the solution is a modification of "bitter".
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Bittern is a source of many salts including magnesium sulfate (epsom salt).
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Multiple methods exist for removing these salts from the bittern, and the method ultimately used depends on the target product.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Products that would naturally precipitate from the bitterns crystallize as evaporation proceeds (e. g. kainite).
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Products that do not preferentially precipitate from bitterns may precipitate through the addition of another compound or through ion exchange.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Potassium-magnesium sulfate double salt, a good fertilizer, is a salt that precipitates from bitterns upon addition of methanol.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Ethanol is also used, but it exhibits a preference for potassium sulfate precipitation.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] The solution can furthermore be used in the production of potash and potassium salts.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Tartaric acid is one compound that can facilitate the precipitation of these salts.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Magnesium hydroxide (Mg(OH)2) can be derived from bittern.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Adding an alkaline solution such as sodium hydroxide (NaOH) or lime will cause magnesium hydroxide to precipitate, although lime is not as effective.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Slower addition of the alkaline solution results in the precipitation of larger particles that are easier to remove from solution.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Nigari is produced from seawater after first removing sodium chloride.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] It contains mostly magnesium chloride, smaller amounts of magnesium sulfate (Epsom salt), potassium chloride, calcium chloride, and trace amounts of other naturally occurring salts.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Nigari was the first coagulant used to make tofu in Japan.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] It is still used today because tofu made using bittern preserves the original flavor of the soybeans used to make it.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Bittern causes rapid coagulation which influences the quality of the tofu.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Alternatively calcium sulfate, calcium chloride or other substances are also used.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Bittern can be used instead of aluminum-based coagulants in the treatment of wastewater produced during the fabric-dyeing process.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] The wastewater pH is basic, which is favorable for the use of bittern.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] After the addition of bittern, precipitated magnesium hydroxide works as the coagulant to collect dye, solids, organic matter, and heavy metals from the wastewater before settling out of solution.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] The sludge produced from this wastewater treatment is also easier to dispose of than sludge produced by aluminum-based coagulants because there are less restrictions surrounding the disposal of magnesium, and it may be possible to recycle the sludge as fertilizer.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Bittern can also be used as a source of magnesium ions (Mg2+) for the precipitation of struvite, a useful fertilizer, from wastewater containing nitrogen and phosphorus.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] One source of useful wastewater is landfill leachate.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Bittern is just as good as other sources of magnesium ions at removing phosphorus from wastewater streams, but it lags behind other magnesium ion sources in terms of the removal of ammonia (a nitrogen compound).
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Bittern can be used to culture *Haloquadratum* archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] *Haloquadratum* are distinctly square-shaped and are abundant in hypersaline environments such as salt ponds.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Their cultivation is necessary for understanding both their ecological function in those environments as well as their unique morphology.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] The presence of *Haloquadratum* in an environment deemed inhospitable for most life has prompted closer study of these archaea.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] A study has been performed exploring the use of bittern as a natural magnesium supplement used to decrease cholesterol spikes after a meal (postprandial hyperlipidemia).
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Due to its high salinity, bittern can also be used as a draw solution for an osmotic process that concentrates sucrose in sugarcane juice.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Because forward osmosis is being used, the process is relatively energy-efficient.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Epsom salt can also be taken from the bittern draw solution once it is used.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] This method is particularly useful in areas where sugarcane and salt production are in close proximity to avoid costs associated with movement of either the sugarcane juice or the bittern.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] In some jurisdictions, most bitterns are used for other production instead of being directly discarded.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] In other jurisdictions each tonne of salt produced can create 3+ tonnes of waste bitterns.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Although bittern generally contains the same compounds as seawater, it is much more concentrated than seawater.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] If bittern is released directly into seawater, the ensuing salinity increase may harm marine life around the point of release.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Even small increases in salinity can disrupt marine species' osmotic balances, which may result in the death of the organism in some cases.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] In December 1997, 94 corpses of green sea turtles, *Chelonia mydas*, were found at the Ojo de Liebre Lagoon (OLL) in Mexico, adjacent to the industrial operation of Exportadora de Sal S.A.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] (ESSA), the largest saltworks in the world.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] The fluoride ion F− content in bitterns was 60.5-fold more than that in seawater.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] The bitterns osmolality was 11,000 mosm/kg of water, whereas the turtle's plasma osmolality was about 400 mosm/kg of water.
[src:bittern-salt/bittern-salt] Researchers concluded that the dumping of bitterns into the ocean should be avoided.
